"BT MAGIC: Schools of Wizardry/MAGIC","THOSE NOT INTERESTED IN MAGIC SHOULD DELETE.


Chris and I were talking about what skills a Wizard would have.  I
personally have no problem with Wizards having overhead- it adds flavor
to the characters.  It also adds flavor that you wouldn't be able to
learn a new Wizardry until you were at least RANK 8(whereupon it doesn't
count against you and if you get your second Wizardry to an 8 you could
learn a third!)

Three ideas in this post:
<A> G:School
<B>STandard Wizard Package
<C>Elven magics.

(A) G: SCHOOL

People can study a Wizardry without keying to something - they learn ""G:
<school>"". They might be waiting until their RANK in their first
Wizardry goes to 8 before thay can key to another one.   When they
finally key,if ever, they get- immediately upon completing the ritual of
keying- half their RANK in ""G:<school>"" as their ""W:""  ie: If they have
RANK 6.4 in ""G: Running Panda school of illusion"", they would perform
the ritual of keying and then they would have a ""W:Illusion"" of RANK
3.2.  

Characters can choose whether to use ""G: Running Panda"" or ""W:Illusion""
as their General skill (since you only get one per roll.	

In this scenario we have been painting Wizards would always have their
Wizardy ""up"" and running all the time at no cost.  

(B) Here is a possible package example:

The school in this example is the Thunder Plateau(TP for short) School
of Evocation in Doria. (The standard Dorian school of Evocation)

Standard <Evocation/Dorian/Thunder Plateau> Wizard Package

AD: Magery Aptitude II-8; 
AD: Sorcerer1-3(Sorceror2 costs 6);
G: <TP>-2
<TP> lore-2; 
R:<TP RUNE SET> lore-3; 
W:<EVOCATION>-3; 
Library Research-1; 
R/w <TP CAST LANG>-2; 
L: <TP CAST LANG>-3; 
Mental End-2; 
History: Magic-2; 
standard <Evocation> sorcery-2;
standard <Evocation> sorcery2-2;
standard <Evocation> sorcery3-2;
<Evocation> spell of choice-2;
<Evocation> Ritual of Choice-2

Total Cost: 30 ISL

""G: TP"" would act as a filter skill to the W: (i.e. for every 2 RANKS in
""W:"" you would need one rank in ""G: TP""

""W: Evocation"" will also act as filter skill in that for every 2 RANKS
in the spell you are casting you need 1 RANK of ""W:""

""ADVANTAGE: Magery Aptitude II"" allows you to key to a school of
Wizardry.  ""Magery Aptitude I"" allows you to use Sorcery, Thaumaturgy,
Alchemy, and Witchcraft

""ADVANTAGE: Sorceror"" Gives you partial familiarity with all sorceries.
It takes away alien and acultural mods(only -30 compared to -90).  Level
2 of this advantage would make you familiar with all sorceries.


(C) Elven magics.

Elves could not be WIzards.  Period. :-)  
NOTE:  We are about to enter the twilight zone- this is all new- created
out of a conversation between Jim and I.  Lara- note- I think Sea-Elves
might be mor elike Humans but we could talk ...

They instead would learn a skill- Call it Pattern Matching.  Pattern
Matching would be a filter skill in that you would have to have your
RANK in PAttern matching be equal to your rank in a ""W:"" or you would
have to roll under it.

You could have as many ""W:""s as you can train, but you do not get the
sapbs automatically and you do not have it on all the time.  

To bring it ""up"" I.e to use a ability or spell of that school, you would
roll under the ""W:"" or ""Pattern Matching"" Whichever was higher:-) and
then ten-counts latyer(base) you would be linked to the pattern of that
Wizardry, and then able to use a sorcery, ability or spell as a skill. 
HOWEVER- it is an active mental action.. so any casting you do would be
at a florentine. (-40 to cast, -2 SPD).

THeir ""SPELLS"" would be unique to them and different form WIzardirc
spells , rites, and rituals in that they would be more like ""Advanced
SOrceries"" or ""Patterneded SOrceries"".  Much more flexible but not as
robust or strong as Human Wizardry.  

You might call these elves ""Pattern Masters"" or somesuch!  Mordanith
