OK. Warning : Blunt opinions ahead.

Out of my conversations with Alex, Chris and Pook.  I am clear that
Alex thinks that this is all fairly clear and that we are starting somewhere

on the same page. I think we will soon be in the same chapter.

This may be over or understating the case but the ""drunken walk""
nature of the conversation is taking a toll on my thought processes.

To try and condense down what I think Alex is aiming for in some sort
of concrete manner:

[1] Alex wants rules (hard numbers) that enforce a specific world view of
wizards.

[2] Wizards are specialists.

[3] Arch-mages (very rare and powerful birds indeed) are masters of three
wizardries.

[4] There is something significant about the learning of a school of
wizardry that confers
some benefits unto the user.  Somewhere in this is the idea of keying
(becoming conversant with the
power-pattern combination  the wizardry represents) and tuning (taking on
the perceptions/worldview
necessary to casting  the wizardries). The process of learning a wizardry
seems to involve some
kineaesthetic learning or flying by the seat of your pants (or Robes, for a
Dorean). In effect , a skill in how to
interface to the power-pattern of the wizardry.

[5] Sorceries underly the wizardries and their usage is not necessarily
impossible
when doing a wizardry but they may be excluded by the nature of the specific
sorcery/wizardry
combination. (Having the fire wizardy worldview active may prevent the
caster from
casting a water sorcery).

[6] Wizardries such as Pyromancy are collections of magical patterns
that confer some energy/efficiency/time/range/duration gains as a result
of being well worn.

[7] More than one school may exist that use the same wizardry.

[8] Studying two schools of the same wizardry would confer no benefits.

The G:/W: split is artificial and muddy. They are used for the same things
in the same situations with no clear difference other than descrioption.

Given the above attributes and assertions I would suggest the following :

W: Pyromancy
       - Purely kineaesthetic navigation (seat-of-the-robe) flying in a
world-view
       that allows the Pyromantic Pattern to be used.

Lore:  Dicks Discount Dorean Pyromantic school
    - Lore needed to interpret the input from W: Dicks Discount Dorean
Pyromantic school
    at an intellectual level. Necessary to design and modify any casting
within the school.

Spoken Casting Language: Dicks Discount Dorean Pyromantic school
    - Dialect of the standard language used for this type of casting.

Written Casting Language: Dicks Discount Dorean Pyromantic school
    - Read/Write dialect of the standard language used for this type of
casting.
    -needed if you are going to learn spells from written descriptions.

Rune Language: The actual reading/writing skills in the rune language
    - needed for drawing/reading these runes.

Lore: Rune Language: The lore about the properties and functions
    of the runes in the rune language.

W: Pyromancy would act as the only allowable general skill.

A character could learn as much of the lore as necessary but the W:
Pyromancy
would need to be separately learned before the college could be of use. In
fact , you could
view the AD: Magic Aptitude as the ability to learn W:Pyromancy. ""Keying""
would occur at the
point that the W: Pyromancy is learned (even at rank 0.1). Of course,
unfamiliarity mods apply.

W: Pyromancy would act as a filter skill in that the rank of the W:Pyromancy
would
govern the effective, default rank that a Pyromantic spell could be cast at.

A wizard with W: Pyromancy = rank 6, and M: Fireball = rank 8 could cast
Fireball at rank 6
by default or make a separate roll against W: Pyromancy in order to cast the
Fireball at full
effectiveness. This would further reinforce the limitations on wizards in
off the cuff casting situations.

Most of the Elven stuff could be made to wok.

