"RE: Ward of Nuryev and the Heartstone Isolation","Well, the easy answer is ""Welcome to the club,"" but that's
E-man's bitterness speaking, not mine, and it isn't particularly
helpful.

1. It is likely that there was an in-game conspiracy to
manipulate Morphus, all suggestive comments aside.

2. It is likely that the other player-characters participated for
their own reasons, some of which they may not have chosen to
share.

3. It is not likely that player-characters conspired to
manipulate Morphus into helping remove the Heartstone so that the
gods could pull the Valhalla thing.

4. It is likely that Alex (not the gods) is taking advantage of
the situation-as-it-exists and (in a Type III reality shift)
having had the gods plan that all along.  One of the better ways
to play all-knowing (or even lots-and-lots-knowing) beings is to
define a lot of their plans retroactively, letting them 'predict'
or 'manipulate' characters when the players are inherently
unpredictable.  I suspect that is what is happening here.

5. I suspect trying to develop a full analytical understanding of
the Machine/Heartstone/Prime relationship is a waste of time.
Learn what you can, get a feel for it, and take your best guess.
I realize that the lack of hard answers is annoying to you as a
player, but many of Alex's philosophical constructs are left
deliberately fuzzy, for several reasons.  First, trying to
develop a finely detailed metaphysics for a world at least as
complex as our own will take infinite time.  Second, I suspect he
doesn't want to leave himself with a strictly mechanistic
universe, but would rather leave some 'wiggle' room so the needs
of the plot can be met.

6. As to the Rismaeon/Symbol/Power thing, I don't think we
anticipated/asked about major Reality shifts like the Valhalla
business.  Given that, Alex is free to implement any result that
will keep the story alive/interesting.

7. Gods use people.  That is one of their functions.  Either
because they are manipulative bastards by nature, or because they
are so used to maneuvering around each other that they know no
other way to behave, or because they see a Higher Vision and feel
that the sacrifice is worth it.  Either way, it's nothing
personal.  Just keep in mind that it is the gods manipulating
Morphus, not Alex manipulating Chris.


Well, that's my take on things.  Hope it helps.

                                              -Myth.
