strong it is depends on environment. In Faery, by the will of Correllan, it
lasts until something better comes along. In the face of competition from
the
outside (like the prime or a competing CGB) it lasts only as long as the elf
can directly maintain it in the face of that competition. In either case the
negotiation/assertion with the reality may take awhile as the elf adjusts
his assertion to the existing reality. It is impolite to interrupt.

[SLIGHT ASIDE] Before starting into that I thought I should mention
something about the word pattern.  It seems to figure heavily into Jim's
concept of elven magic.  I would assert that wizardry patterns refer to
Kua-Toa created.  Specifically all of the human wizardries are called power
patterns becuase they have some aspect of Order magic in them (even Illusion
which is why humans do not go insane casting it - although the order magic
here is probably the slimmest of frameworks).  As far as the other types of
magic I would say that Dreaming does not really fit the word pattern, it is
a fundamentally different thing.  Where Slaad influences have appeared in
the human wizardries it is like a mold or a virus or a taint on the
underlying Ordered framework and in the case of Illusion the infection is
bigger than the thing it infects.  In a similar sense I would say that
Draconic magic is so fundamentally different than Order magic that a pure
draconic archetype would never be described as a pattern (although there may
be achetypical patterns or archetypical patterners as well as infected
archetypes and archetypical infections).  What I am trying to do is
establish the fundamental difference between the types of magic.

I would disagree. All castings have a pattern OR produce a pattern. Human
wizardries are neat because they have a ~fixed pattern and
produce a ~fixed pattern. Draconic castings produce a pattern (specific to
that cast at that point in reality) that could be interacted
with though there is little to no underlying pattern to the process. Elven
castings are in between. The pattern of the cast exists but adapts
throughout the cast to what is being done. The end result is a usually a
fixed pattern that doesn't last without outside aid.

