"Re: BTR.6 : Gun and System Questions","More commentary... Here is my guns manifesto...

Barrel Length Mods:
   You have already got a fairly sever (not necessarily inaccurate)
system for range mods, and longer barrel weapons will have longer
ranges.  You have penalized both chance to hit and damage as a function
of range.  Adding a % difference to the base chance based on barrel
length effectively penalizes short barrel weapons in a third way.  I
agree with the idea, I just think it has been sufficiently modeled.  I
also like no mods because it is easy to remember.  If you really feel
the average gun should have a less than zero chance to be used by an
untrained person (without stance, set-up etc) then I suggest a uniform
-10% or whatever works.

Range Mods:
   The % to hit mods for distance seem good (as long as you intend that
nobody would waste the lead on an extra-long range shot).  I still have
a problem with the damage mod at extra long range.  At -16, a level 5
person firing a pistol of moderate power (a .357), if they made 1/2
their % chance (at a -160%) would do full damage of exactly zero
points.  The a fully successful shot from a reasonably skilled gunman
with a decent gun would bounce off the target.  I'm sure it would sting
a little though, but only if it is not a ""glancing blow.""  I would
propose a -8 mod to damage as being sufficient in conjunction with a
-160% chance.  (BTW, the M-16 arguement is a bit of a tangent.  The fact
that an M-16 is not effective at long distances means that it has a
shorter range than a long barreled rifle.  Your mods apply to each gun
at its own individual extra long range--a very different number of feet
for each weapon!)
   Oh yeah, and I think 2x damage at point blank range is just too
disgusting (except maybe for a shotgun).  A +40 to hit will give boost
level of success from miss to grazing to success to crit, thereby giving
more damage.  If you want to add a +4 to damage to make it even grosser
I won't complain, but people will drop like flies with double damage.

Target Angular Movement Mods:
   In my relatively simple system I apply full mods for a target
traveling between 90 and 45 degrees of the shooter, half mods for 45 to
""close to 0"" and no mods if the target is moving (relatively) straight
toward or away from the shooter.  For your more ""granular"" system, you
could apply (Angle + 10)% of the mods.  In other words, a target
traveling perpendicular would be 90 + 10 = 100% = full mods, and a
straight on target would be 0 + 10 = 10% = 1/10th the mods.  It is
logical but cumbersome--you'll probably like it ;-)

Target Velocity Movement Mods:
   I think the target velocity movement mods may be too high, or that
there may be a better model.  No police data for you, but based on my
paintball experience it seems too high.  I have been hit, and have hit
plenty of people while the target in question was running/sprinting.  I
don't set up set up significantly and have no other gun skills.  Lets be
generous and make me rank 4, and generous again and give me another 10%
in Dex/MCF and THB, and put me in stance.  I have a total of 60%
(assuming my paintball gun is actually a long barrel rifle, which it is
not--for a short barrel this only gets worse).  A sprinter will cover
6'/ct for a -60%.  Additionally they are moving, another -30%.
Statistically none of us novices should ever have hit anyone unless they
were standing still.  And a paintball gun is a pretty crappy weapon.  I
suggest this--keep the -10% per foot per count, but drop the -30% for a
moving target.  Replace the -30% with a rule like, no set up unless you
make a successful tracking roll.  The reason it is so easy to hit a
stationary target (vs. a moving target) is that you can set up, and do
not have to move your hand arm to track as you fire.  You have already
covered the tracking with the mods for angular movement (described
above) which you are certain to implement ;-), all that's left is the
set-up.
   I do like the fact that running is now more effective vs guns than
activating defense.  I still think defense against a gun (except maybe
at point blank range) is a pretty silly concept.  The army teaches
soldiers 3 second dashes to cover, not ""float like a butterfly, sting
like a bee.""

Speed Points:
   OK as a math athiest I can handle the 2 for 1 buy-down and the 10 for
1/2 speed buy-down system.  Beyond that my head starts to hurt.  Every
time I want to speed up an action I will slow down the game.  I second
Mark's comment.  Good enough--leave it alone.  I also think you do not
want to institute the
10-points-buys-you-1/2-and-2-points-per-one-thereafter system.  This
would actually make it proportionally harder to speed up a long slow
action, and proportionally easier to speed up an already fast action.
If Chuck and Stephen (and probably Mordanith and Morpheus) are grossing
you out with fractional count actions, how about 10 buys you 1/2, 20
buys you 1/4, 40 buys you 1/8, 80 buys you 1/16?  It is similar at the
low end of high speed actions, but puts a damper on things getting too
ridiculous.

Gun Quick Strike:
   I now understand how gun speeds work, thanks.  If it makes a
difference, in important situations I will almost certainly want three
separate rolls.  What is the distinction between the 4 ct targeting time
and MCF set-up?  Is it the basic minimum time needed to target in order
to fire at zero mods?  If so, what is the penalty for ""shooting from the
hip"" or taking a snap-shot?  Presumably there would be a skill that
would offset these penalties.  A successful quick strike roll would
reduce the time needed for targeting and a snapshot skill would reduce
the mods for firing without taking targeting time.

Other Stuff:
   I am not sure about Mark's suggestion for the application of
Acrobatic Combat.  It certainly should apply to striking while jumping,
being thrown, etc., but I do not know about the 3% vs. 6%.  What skills
give 6% per rank?  I only know of specific Called Shot skills.  A +6% is
pretty powerful unless the mods are pretty severe.  I would almost
suggest making everything +3% again and softening some of the most
severe mods.
   An interesting observation.  If I have a high Punch and Pankido
skill, and want to increase my chance to quick-strike, do a called shot
head, and block, what are the skills I should take?  The answer?  Kick!
Kick will give me a +3% to each of these punching actions while the
specific support skill only gives +3 to that particular action.  That
does not feel right to me.  Support skills should contribute more than
secondaries.  My suggestions would be to allow support skills to
contribute more than secondaries (which would get ugly with all BT's
carefully balanced mods) or alternatively broaden the scope of each
support skill.  Turn skills into MCF quickstrike, PCF called shot head,
etc.  That way you at least get a little more return for your
investment, even if it is still better to take secondaries.
   And one last question.  Do support skills (like quick strike or
called shot) get secondaries?

   There was probably more, but my fingers hurt.  I didn't realize how
much I missed good game design discussions.

