"More Gun & General BT Thoughts","OK, here's my rebuttal about barrel length and extra long range, then
I'll shut up.

Barrel Length:
   If you stood 5 feet from the end of my gun and held perfectly still,
I do not believe I would be 25% more likely to hit you with a long rifle
than with a short pistol.  I understand and agree with the fact that
range mods are by caliber of ammo, and that weapon length increases
accuracy.  Why not make barrel length modify range?  You could do your
muzzle velocity calculation for range, then add or subtract 10% of that
value for each increment of barrel length, for example.

Extra-Long Range:
   Sure, ask the martial artists and mages if anybody is worried about
extra-long gun ranges ;-)  The fact is that if you establish a range,
you should expect that people are going to try to use it.  The other
problem I have with the current system is that it is not consistent.  A
short pistol is completely useless, damage wise, at extra long range
(-16 to damage), but a .50 cal weapon would still do a fair amount of
damage at extra long range.  Before you argue that heavy calibers are
more effective at longer distances, keep in mind that ranges are already
a function of caliber.  A .50 cal will have a much longer distance for
XL range than a small caliber.  There should be a distance for both
weapons (the end of extra long range) where the round will do an average
of zero damage.  Here are three mechanisms that I think would be more
realistic (if more complex).
   Decrease damage proportionally by range.  For example, 3/4 damage at
medium range, 1/2 at long range, 1/4 at extra long range.  This has the
same problem but to a lesser degree, but is fairly simple to apply.
   I like this one better if you can make it work.  You know how called
shot mods come off your chance, but go back onto your chance to crit?
Could you apply range mods to increase your chances of a ""grazing"" shot
instead of a full damage shot?
   My current favorite.  Subtract damage per foot.  Say -1 dam per
200'.  This would make a Walther (avg dam = 15) -6 to -12 at the
beginning and end of extra long range.  A Browning .357 would be 17 -7
to -15.  Each would do a couple points at the end of extra long range.
If that is too much you could look at 150'.  I don't know about your
ranges/damages for high cal long rifles, but at 200' one mile would be
-26, at 150' it would be -35.  The disad is keeping track of the
distance of the target (in feet vs. just range).  The advantage is that
it is a more linear, and I think from what you have described, a more
realistic system.

Movement Mods:
   A -5% with a -20% base seems much more reasonable.  And I was not
complaining--I was complimenting you on a system improvement ;-)
   What all the mods for the shooter?  Move speed, unstable platform,
defense activated, etc.?

Speed Points:
   I took your basic idea for speed points and, but I changed it
somewhat.  Five points will drop you action to 3/4 speed, 10 drops it to
half.  Another 10 drops it to half again (1/4 total), etc.  I like this
better (for my system anyway) because all skills are decreased
proportionally.  The way I understand the BT system, it is actually
easier to speed up quick actions than slow ones.  To drop a 32 count
action to 1/4 of its speed would cost 10 (drops to 16) plus 10 X 8
(drops to 8) for a total of 90 speed points to get to 1/4 speed.  To
drop a 4 count action to 1/4 speed would cost 10 + 10 = 20.  Did I do
that right?  If so, I think this is a major problem.
   If I understand your system, then I do propose a change.  How about
10 drops you to 1/2, 20 (total) to 1/4, 40 (total) to 1/8th, etc.?  Play
with that if you do not like the exact numbers.  I agree that all skills
should follow the same rules as much a possible.  The above system
should work for all the ""hard to buy down"" skills.

Questions:
   What do general skills (ie. Pankido) do?  They add 3% per rank.  I
heard they also add damage and speed?  I also seem to remember Chuck
""activating"" his Pankido.  Is that still part of the system?  If so,
what does activating do for you?
   What kinds of support skills are there and how do they work.  I know
of some that increase a chance for a specific action, most of which
offset penalties (like Called Shot).  I know of some which give you
points (like Quick Strike).  Are there other types?  You can increase
the effect of Quick Strike by rolling against it.  Does it do anything
for you if you miss or do not roll?  Can you roll against a skill like
Called Shot?  If so, what does it do for you?  Are skills other than
specific area called shot skills that add 6% per rank?

   If you can answer all of these questions, I think I will know
everything I need to know in order to shoot someone again! ;-)

