characters with a low stat.  It may convince all but the really hardcore
roleplayers not to even consider a below average stat.  A compromise
might be Stat-10, *2 if positive or *1 if negative.

Speed Points:
   For the sake of simplicity and sanity, in my system I have set the
base speed of any action as the time it takes an average person to do an
action with an average quality result, whether it is building a house or
throwing a punch.  It should require extra luck, skill, and/or the
sacrifice of quality to decrease the time of the action, and it should
be exponentially more difficult to make a task shorter and shorter.  Of
course I hate exponentials, so I tried to come up with something
similar.  The net result is that most people can cut an action to 3/4 or
1/2 and still have some chance of success.  People cutting a skill to
1/4 have to be very good/lucky.
   BT generates more speed points than my system so this is a bit
awkward, but a rough translation to BT might be--1 SP buys off 1 count
until you reach 10 SP (=3/4 speed) or 20 SP (=1/2 speed, round up).
Thereafter, 2 SP buys off 1 count until 40 (=1/4 speed).  Then 4 SP buys
off one count until 80 (=1/8 speed).  You must pay the larger cost, so
cutting a 2 count action to 1 count would automatically cost 20.  I
realize it defies some laws of physics and is not a completely smooth
system, but it seems to play well and cover a pretty broad range of
action durations.  Your mileage may vary.

