   I like the fact that body size has more to do with HTK in the new
system.  Drive has a very minimal effect on HTK.  Just an observation.
     
<Myth>

If HTK is used as a measure of physical (ie, structural) damage, then drive 
shouldn't really be a factor at all; determined people are just as injured 
as non-determined ones.  I would think the difference to be in how they 
react to injury, with the more-determined person better able to ignore an 
injury.

If, on the other hand, you want to have HTK damage measure the efficiency 
drop due to injury, then DR should be included, and Willpower saves should 
probably not be allowed.


<Jeff>

Stats & Level Factors:
   I also like the increase in importance of stats (like you couldn't
guess that), but Chris is right that it is pretty harsh on low level 
characters with a low stat.  It may convince all but the really hardcore 
roleplayers not to even consider a below average stat.  A compromise 
might be Stat-10, *2 if positive or *1 if negative.
     
<Myth>

A couple of points, not all in reference to Jeff's comments:

1) Low-stat characters will be somewhat penalized by not getting the bonus 
that high-stat characters get.  This will serve as somewhat of a deterrent 
already, particularly is people are just looking at it as a way to et 
points.  I think additional penalties fall into the 'punitive damages' 
category and might well be unnecessary.

2) I like the idea of one formula for level factor, without special cases 
for below ten, or already-high level factor or whatever.  

3) I am immediately suspicious of rule changes made to help (or restrict) 
certain kinds of characters.  The fact is that clumsy people play sports 
badly, or at least less well than non-clumsy people of the same skill 
level.  Intelligent people have an easier time learning history people than 
others.  Characters with low stats will have problems, and the payer should 
know that going in.  After that, let the dice fall where they may.


<Jeff>

