"BTR.6: Books, spell crystals, and data storage","A funny thing happened to me on the way home from a run Sunday night.
Bestowed upon me was the knowledge of how books and spell crystals would
probably be run.  Alex requested I send it to the list for your comments.

Alex wants to have books, spell crystals and similar items have an effect
through training.  Each would have three variables:

1) Author's rank in Teaching filtered through some type of text-book design
   skill.  This would give the book's ""Teachers Rank in Teaching"" (TRT).

2) Author's rank in the skill(s) that you wish to train in filtered through
   the author's reading/writing skills.

3) The length of the book.  This would give the maximum number of hours that
   could be gained from the book or crystal (ie. you can't study just one
   basic text on Geomancy to become Rank 20 without doing anything else)

Once this process is determined, it should be possible to quickly generate
the books, crystals, CD-ROM's, memory wafers, etc. that we find during
adventuring.  

A few items that I would like to throw in:

A) My suggestion below would be the exception, not the rule.  Most books
   would be generated like this one:
   ""Geomancy by Kheldar""
   TRT = 4 (Either Kheldar was a lousy teacher or just poor in textbook
design)
   Effective Rank in Geomancy = 12 (kheldar was good at Geomancy and writing)
   Length of Book = 100 hours of training

B) It is entirely possible that a book might provide multiple  benefits.  
   For example, a book on ""Traditional Ward Structures of Dorian Mages"" might
   contain a background of warding concepts, a general discussion of basic
   spell constructs, an example of major and minor wards, and some discussion
   of the history of warding.  This would translate to the ability to train
   in W:Warding or W:Abjuration (possibly at a decreased percentage), the
   ability to train in a couple sorcery Ward's, a Spell (M:) and a 
   Ritual (R:), and Warding Lore.

C) I suggest that a comparison of your skill rank and the books skill rank
   determine whether you can use it or not just like in regular training.  
   For example, a rank 1 book shouldn't be very useful to someone with a
   rank 9 skill.  A rank 4 book could be used by someone with a rank 5 skill
   because it is within 20% of the trainee's rank (per Alex's training rules).
   Of course, there is always the possibility that there is something unique
   in a specific book.  The GM should determine this however.

D) I'd also like to suggest that most books have a usage length related to
   rank.  Some books might have a rank 4.  I might need to have a minimum
   rank of 2 in order to use the information in the book and not be able to
   use it after I go beyond rank 5.  I might also need rank 4 in a rune set
   or written language in order to use that particular book.

E) Most books might just have the ability to give you enough training to get 
   to rank 1 in a skill.  After all, how often would you expect to find a book
   that could teach you how to rip a hole in the fabric of reality?

Chris
