Good idea.  Advanced students won't get much from basic texts.  Perhaps the 
""with partner"" rules might apply if the book and student are close enough in 
level.  If texts are general, they might be expert on aspects of the field 
that a student might not have mastered; the studious bodyguard, fresh from the 
military, might only need to brush up on his trap knowledge and (sadly) skip 
the section on contract law entirely.
     
>> D) I'd also like to suggest that most books have a usage length related to
   rank. <<
     
Hmmm.  Another good point.  Most books will be written for a target 
audience.  Calculus texts will assume that the reader is familiar with more 
basic maths.  Badly written books might miss this target.  Perhaps removing 
a rank of Book Teaching Skill for each difference of 1 between the students 
intended rank and his actual rank?  (Not sure I like that, but it's 
simple.)

The limitation on reading the book also seems logical.  Some sort of 
reading skill roll should probably be made, with the effective rank 
determining how much of the book is assimilated.

     
     All in all, an interesting set of ideas.
     
