 I just finished reading through the pre-release of version 6.0, and I
have a couple comments, mostly minor.  Of course, please disregard
anything that has changed in the released version.

I like the fact that STM is now an average (surprise, surprise).  I
think that is more representative of the number of XP invested in a
character regardless of their distribution across level factors.  It is
also easier to calculate.

I think it is possible to teach a skill to someone who has a higher rank
in the skill, particularly for physical skills.  Consider a coach for an
olympic athelete.  The coach would probably have a very high rank, but
the competing athlete would likely have a higher one.  Maybe you could
modify learning time by 15 min * (students skill rank - teacher's skill
rank), with the student's skill not to exceed the teachers skill plus
rank in teaching.  It seems trivial, but when you have people at high
levels training with good teachers, it may be important.

I still think Horsemanship belongs in VHF :-)  It is basically knowledge
of steering a large (animate) vehicle and knowing the types of terrain
it can handle, turning radius, etc.  Just like a motorcycle or other
vehicle, if you fail your roll, THEN you need AGL to stay on.  (Much
harder for a horse than a car!).  Also, I imagine cart/chariot driving
is a VHF skill, and I would think they ought to be related to
Horsemanship pretty closely.

Here's the big one:  Speed.  I would like to propose several changes to
the speed system.  The system you wrote up is different in effect from
the one I proposed, and I also have had some other thoughts.  Here
goes...

First (with some admitted self interest on this one), I think MCF should
go into speed.  When you originally wrote the speed formula you were
probably thinking about bows and slings, and maybe snipers, but not Wild
West style gunslingers or Dangerous Jazz style commando shootouts.  I
imagine this is a similar line of reasoning to the one that added SCF to
speed.

Second, I think the splitting of speed into action and reaction is
awkward.  That change seemed to be a patch-job to keep high reaction
speeds under control, and I think it could be taken care of with some
other system changes.  I think much of the problem is that it is much
easier to accumulate negative initiative than it is to suffer the
minuses to hit or to damage.  I think you can re-tune your speed point
system to allow low level characters some chance of speeding up actions
while preventing high level characters from acting in 1/8th counts, and
simplify the system at the same time.  I propose the followining:

One speed point is generated by 1 pt negative initiative, a -5% to hit,
or a -1 to damage.  One-for-one reduction of positive initiative to
zero.  Beyond zero, 10 pts drops an action to 3/4 speed, 20 (total)
drops it to half speed, 40 (total) drops it to quarter speed, 80 (total)
drops it to eighth speed.  Low level characters could afford 3/4 or
maybe half speed with luck or some sacrifice of speed/dam.  High level
characters could do half pretty easily, maybe a quarter, but would be
very hard pressed to reach eighth speed.  This gives you a limitless
system (so you don't have to make arbitrary rules about how ""the fastest
an action can be is XXX."") but keeps the scale fairly compressed so that
high level characters aren't acting in fractional counts all the time.
You can also just add your speed points up and spend them without
worrying about halving reaction speed (it has been effectively halved by
buying you half as much compared to damage and chance to hit).  It also
is pretty easy to remember:  20, 40, 80 = 1/2, 1/4, 1/8.

What do you think?

PS.  If you have not caught it already, you have the old (old) version
of the speed point formula in the combat section.

