[Jeff]
The way BT is run, speed can be used on ANY action.  In theory, every 
level factor could be argued to contribute to speed.  A jazz guitarist, 
for example, needs to react quickly to play those spiffy riffs and keep 
up with the ever changing improvisation.  In actual play though, when is 
speed really important?  When your life is in danger.  In a combat 
situation.  That is when speed is really important, and I believe people 
who are in lots of combat situations react more quickly because their 
lives depend upon developing that ability.  That is why PCF and AGF 
should contribute to speed.  High speed chases justify VHF.  And I think 
that missile and magical combat is just as deadly, and those who engage 
in it should be faster.  If anything, I would drop DXF since speed is 
not a critical part of most DXF skills.

[Myth]
I think 'combat reflexes', or whatever you want to call them (""pilot 
reflexes"" in the Liaden books) should be a separate issue from speed 
points.

Speed points seem to model the way highly-learned skills make one faster 
to act when doing those skills, and having a bunch of highly-learned 
skills makes one faster overall than someone without them.

This whole combat reflexes issue, OTOH, seems to be implying that people 
who have had to react for their life are consistently faster than those 
who haven't.  To me, this would seem like an Advantage, to be handled 
under the Ad/Disad system.  Call it 'Faster Reaction', have it give one 
SPD per level, and price it prohibitively enough so people only develop 
it after years in the field (when it is cheaper than raising your 
Assault Rifle another level, for instance).

Just a thought.


