For what it is worth, I agree with your relative ratings of PCF, VHF and
AGF, and most of your arguments about the other level factors.  However,
in play, speed is USED by people in all classes.  It is critical to
shooters in a gunfight and mages in a mage duel, even though magic
doesn't even have a physical aspect to it!  What does it matter to a
mage's reaction time if he can punch people quickly?  Since you USE
speed for the complete spectrum of skills, and since it can be critical
(as in life or death) for people using a wide range of skills, I think a
wide range of level factors should contribute (although maybe even at
lesser percentages than AGF).

I also think you are very biased toward PHYSICAL speed and toward
martial arts (just because you like them so much).  Although most of the
actions that require tracking counts and speed points are physical and
combat related, it is a mistake to assume they are the only ones
important enough to model.  You realize that except for DSC, there is
absolutely no representation of mental speed, yet half of your level
factors are based on speed.  Try telling Borealis that speed is not
important when he is trying to jam a comm signal or deactivate a bomb. 
Try telling Mordanith that speed is not important to him because it is
only based on physical actions.  In case I have not been clear :-) I
think there is a big difference in your personal concept of what speed
is compared to the way you apply it in actual gaming.

I am also very much against having an action and reaction speed.  As I
said earlier, accumulated system changes and higher level characters
have made it obvious that speed points are too easy to get.  Rather than
create two types of speed, or split the old number in half and use two
sets of rules for each half, why not just divide the whole formula by 2
and use the points as is?  That way you do one calculation when you make
your spreadsheet and/or manually update your character rather than using
a fractional stat in play.

OK, enough ranting...

Joe called as I was finishing this e-mail and we discussed this whole
issue.  Of course, he agrees with me completely ;-)  And actually, we
generated some food for thought.

Considering all the above arguments, the most realistic thing to do
within BT might be to go to level factor based speeds.  Your speed would
be, say level factor over 10 or level factor over 5.  Forget about base
speed because each action would use the level factor speed most
appropriate.  Then you would add your rank in your skill.  If you want
to reflect crossover (martial artists quicker at shooting guns, etc.)
you could have a physical base speed and a mental base speed.  You would
then add, say physical or mental base speed, level factor over 10, and
rank-2 to get total speed points for each action.  And as MY personal
bias, I would still throw DSC into physical speed to reflect the need to
figure out what the hell is going on before you can react.

There.  Hopefully you are now unenrolled.  Your refund is in the mail
;-)

