"Re: BT Rev 6A -SPEED - Please respond!","This is a summary of a discussion between Alex, Joe and me about speed,
and some more food for thought (as if you weren't full already ;-)

After much discussion, I believe the three of us agreed:
1) Trying to model speed sucks.  It is very hard to base it on any hard
data from real life, so the best option is to go for what ""feels right""
and works well from a game balance point of view.
2) People generally first go through a reaction phase, in which they
figure out what is going on.  People are more likely to figure this out
quickly and more accurately if they have a high discernment and/or if
they are familiar with the type of situation they are in.
3) People then choose a response and execute it.  Certainly expertise in
the skill and similar skills helps them act more quickly.  Possibly
other factors help to lesser degrees.
4) Physical skills probably should not greatly affect speed of mental
actions and vice versa.
5) I think we even all agreed that the current BT system unfairly
emphasizes only physical skill even though it is to all skills, physical
and mental.

Here is a proposal for a new method of calculating speed points.  This
is not meant to be the perfect system, but should be a good starting
point for discussion:

At the risk of making things too simple for Alex ;-) I would propose not
making the distinction between reaction and action, but including
elements of both in one pool of speed point as the current system does.

Speed points would be: STM/2 + LVL FACTOR/4 + SKILL-2 + SECONDARIES, ETC

Or to include DSC:  (STM + DSC)/4 + LVL FACTOR/4 + SKILL-2 + 2NDRY, ETC

Using STM reflects the idea (particularly Joe's) that all skills help a
person to see patterns more quickly and understand situations more
clearly.  It also crosses the division between mental and physical
skills, allowing both to contribute.  DSC if included reflects the
persons natural ability to see and understand patterns.  If there were
to be a separate reaction phase, STM and DSC would probably be heavily
involved (although they are just added into the pool in this system). 
The skill and secondaries are as in the current system, for all the same
reasons.

The other big change outside of STM is using a level factor.  It would
be whichever level factor is most appropriate to the situation.  If you
are sparring it is PCF, if you are in a mage duel it is SCF.  It would
be the level factor of whatever skill you chose to use for your upcoming
action.

Here is another twist that would simplify things (but probably too much
for the level of detail in BT):  Instead of LEVEL FACTOR/4, use LEVEL
FACTOR/2, but no longer let secondaries and tertiaries contribute to
speed or damage.  Use LVL FACTOR/2 for both.  This would cut down on the
number of calculations of fractional speed and damage points that need
to be done in play (but does not reflect the fact that some skills
within a level factor may have better secondaries than others).  Just a
thought.

A quick mental exercise made it look like any of these proposed formulae
would keep average speed points in the same ballpark as they are now,
but they would be considerably higher for specialists in their level
factor of expertise, and maybe notably lower for people in areas in
which they have no skill.  I would be interested to know how anybody
else's characters would come out with this system, particularly lower
level characters.
