While I liked the speed formula a lot last week, I spent a bunch of time
stewing over it this weekend, and now I'm having some pretty serious
second thoughts. Here are my cogitations:

1) Why should a very learned scholar have fast reflexes? Or for that
matter, an accomplished artist or technician? Personally, I don't think
that my ranks/experience in  my technical field have any bearing
whatsoever on my speed of reflex.

2) We point to certain people (athletes, pilots, etc) as having fast
reflexes. I don't think it is true that they DEVELOP them, I think that
having them is a PREREQUISITE to being in the fields that they are in.

I know that people have been arguing (Jeff ;-) That musicians (for
instance) need speed to do their thing- I don't really think that this
is true. What musicians need is timing, not raw speed. Remember that the
scale of speed that we are talking about here is very small- sub-second
range. And why should a musician be faster at ducking a thrown bottle?
(Don't answer that!! ;-)

>I like the STM/3 change.  When you reduced the effect of level factor to
>LVF/10 I was afraid that the system would favor high level characters
too much over lower level specialists.  The STM/3 change addresses this

You think this is true? Do you realize that Stephen is faster than Chuck
in PCF skills? 

Here is where I was headed, tell me if I'm crazy.

1) Speed is based far more on Stats than has been accounted for. Who
have some of the fastest reflexes/action speeds around? Teenagers. While
they lack the DSC to always make the RIGHT action, they still make some
fo the fastest actions.

2) STM is too broad. I just can't buy into it. The old weighted system
was better. Also, it is a double kicker- a high facter adds twice, once
to STM, and then again directly.

3) I think the factor addition is still too small.

So I was thinking something more like: (the factors may need tweaking- I
don't like the /8 either, but 10 is too much and 5 is too small)

(DSC - 10)/2 + (AGL-10)/2 + LVF/8

This is more heavily stat based and more heavily SPECIFIC skill based-
it will keep those damned bookworms and mages from winning at slappsies.
What do you think?


