> SIGH- please number crunch this if you get a chance:
> 
> (DSC - 10)/2 + STM/10 + LVF/5 - 3

If you get rid of the -3 (which you should do) Stephen comes out a few
points lower in speed in his best LVFs than he is in the current system.
Based on Stephen, my one data point, I would suggest:
    (DSC - 10)/2 + STM/5 + LVF/5
This would put him right where he currently is in his best LVFs and
several points lower in the others. 

I think you have to make a decision about complexity versus realism.  We
can argue forever finding ridiculous examples on the edge of any model,
asking why one remote skill should affect another.  I think there is
enough of a belief in the influence of ""general life experience"" to
justify putting STM in if you feel it should be in there, granting that
it is never going to be a perfect model.

If you are willing to go one step more complex, I think one area of
general agreement, and the focal point of all the ""why should skill X
influence skill Y"" arguements is the division between mental and
physical skills.  I have chosen to make this split in my system, and I
think BT would support it well.  LVFs are already divided into mental
and physical.  If you wanted to go this route you could even adapt the
above formula (mine, of course, not yours ;-) by calculating a
""mini-STM"" for mental and physical LVFs (like an average of all physical
LVFs and an average of all mental LVFs):

   Physical speed = (DSC-10)/2 + ""Phys STM""/5 + LVF/5
   Mental speed = (DSC-10)/2 + ""Mental STM""/5 + LVF/5

Or if you want to keep some influence of life experience in physical
skills affecting mental and vice versa, you could do something like:

   Physical speed = (DSC-10)/2 + STM/10 + Phys STM/10 + LVF/5

This stacks the deck more and more in favor of the specific skill and
type of skill (physical vs. mental), but still keeps the STM concept.  I
have a dire prediction to make about going _too_ far in this direction,
but I think I'll wait to see if anyone actually mentions it...
