"BTR6A - the Speed Formula","Ahem!  Wow!  Great conversation.   Thanks to everyone who contributed.  
The proposed new speed formulaS(2 of them) are at the bottom of the
post.  This is a long but worthwhile post (please read and respond to 
if you can)

My guess as to Geoff's Dire Prediction:  ""Gee, you know the old speed
formula did that really well with its layed-out level factors. 
Let's just go back to that!"":-):-)

I like what Myth did.  ""Let me explain.  No, not enough time, let me 
sum up!""

Our intention is to derive a formula that will give us a number which
we can use to model the time it takes anyone to react to stimuli in 
ANY situation.  Okay. 

We had one. It was:
(DSC + AGL -20)/2 + PCF/10 + VHF/10 + AGF/10 + DXF/10 + SCF/20

But NOOOOO.. that wasn't good enough!;-)  Some people correctly pointed
out that we were using that formula for every type of speed and it made
martial artists and drivers faster at calculus.  So we began looking 
at alternatives.  At the time, in my all-seeing and all-knowing wisdom, 
 I flatly rejected having two speeds.  Ahem....

The objects we have to work with to create this new number are:
The character's Statistics. 
The level factors associated with the action(s) being performed.
The skill being utilized.
The skills closely related to those skills(secondaries)
The person's general experience in life.  
Situational modifiers(physical/mental state, time flow rate:-), etc.)

Let me now state somethings that appear to be generally agreed upon,
some of which we even have more than anecdotal evidence for!;-)

(1) Fast people are fast.  Slow people are slow.
  
*SIGH*  This profound, yet true, truth does appear to have some 
correlate in the real world.  Unfortunately I think people in real 
life do have structural and programmed in speeds which guide what 
kind of professions they go into etc.  Do I think people can learn to be
fast? Yes. Do I, against what I naively think is fair, beleive that
faster people can be trained to be even faster than slower people?  
YEP.  Therefore in a realism model- stats would be VERY important to
speed and would provide somesort of horrible cap as Mark suggested.
I am willing to model stats being important- but will not model the 
cap on player fun principles.

(2) People are fastest in their specialty skills. 

I think we can all agree that some combination of LVF and SKill and
secondaries should be the greatest component of SPD.  I personally think
that in the highest levels LVF could give more SPD points than the skill
itself.  I think as people move up in an area of skill they begin to 
master the principole disticntions in the area and start inventing
actions and skills from the concepts behind it.  Did that make any
sense?  All I am saying is LVF is important. 

(3) Older people are NOT faster. If anything they are slower. 

I give.  Uncle.  Stop hititng me with reality. It hurts.
  
(4) Do people get faster in all skills as they develop expertise in one?

[Myth]  Well, ther's the rub.  I don't think so, other people do.
[Alex]	i want to think that!  Please Auntie Em!  DAMN!  Here is the
honest to God truth as I know it (in other words- my opinion!:-)): 
I don't think so either.  

Unfortunately there is limited interaction between widely divergent
skill areas.  Tech writers do not have higher reaction speeds as far as
I can tell.  I know tech writers who seem to be physically fast but they
are martial artists or athletes.  I know tech writers who seem to be 
physically slow- and they are not martial
artists and athletes.  Hmmmm..... 

HOWEVER:  I do think there is sufficient bleedover between physical
skills that someone who is a fast martial artist will be quicker at
catching a ball out of the air, or even... picking a lock?  Shooting a
bow?   *SHRUG*  
 
I think it might be worth having (God it is so painful agreeing with
Geoff so much!;-)) a physical speed and a mental speed.  Or rather i
think it is worth having one SPEED formula but have it use:
(a) either physical or mental STM
(b) the appropriate LEVEL Factor
(c) (DSC and INT) for mental; and (DSC and AGL) for physical?

Then primaries skill would give (RANK - 2), and secondaries and general 
skills give (Rank - 2)/2. 

If we accept that, the question becomes one of scale/weighting both for
realism and for playability.  Remember inititive is rolled on 2d6, so
half of what this formula generates in an average, medium scale 
character should not be higher than 6 or so INCLUDING RANK MODS!

What is most important: Primary skill?  I think, at the very least 
that is what we want to model.  So, at normal levels the primary skill
should have the most influence.(Obviously if someone has a 30 Agility
or a 193 LVF the primary skill may occasionally get overshadowed!:-)) 

Let us look at the formula.
(c) STATS: 
The standard formula for stat influence is (STAT - 10)/x  where
X is often 2.  With two stats (DSC + INT - 20)/2 generates a range 
from -8 to +8 speed.  Your average starting BT character will have a 
3 SPD based on stats.  That sounds okay... 8 is a lot and it requires 
2 18s.  This would be too large for me but remember the stat
conversation above.  However it may be too large as stats figure
prominantly in the Level Factors and STMs.  If we go with the /2 a 
volley ball player of RANK 10 with a 10 DSC and AGL would be the same
speed as a RANK 2 volleyball player of 18 DSC and AGL. Does that 
sound right?  That is an uncomfortable strenth of stat for me though 
it is an extreme case...

(b) LEVEL FACTOR:
I think it is clear from our conversations that the appropriate LVF-
the one for the skill grouping being used is important.
If we use LVF/5[/2, /4, /5, or /10 are just so much easier than other 
divs...) then a person with a LVF of 10(first level character:-)) would
have 2 spd points from that.   An LVF 50(quite a high level character)
would have 10 spd points and be faster then stats would give a double 18
person. A LVF 100 person(extraordinarily high level) would have 20 spd
points.  When you crunch the numbers for likely RANKs to generate those
kinds of Level Factors  that measn somewhere around 60 or 70 LVF the 
level factor becomes more influential than the skill itself in speed.  
Truthfully- I am okay with that.  LVF/10 gives obviously a smaller
spread.   It would have the primary skill be more important until you
were well into the 100s.   Lets go with that.  Say LVF/10.

(c) STM
*SOB*  *WHINE* CRY!!!!!   SOme of us (Jim and I) think STM is an
important addition to SPEED.  But, the majority of you disagree and 
even went so far as to produce well-thought-out arguments against.
So there.  I think it is worth including an STM.  Let us have a physical
and a mental STM(I am convinced that whatever bleedover there is is not
worth modeling between mental and physical).  By the way there are
skills which could go either way, right?  You could even argue VHF could
go either way, right?  Too bad!:-) Also notice this will make MLF and
PLF smaller than STM was.  You caused this!:-):
MLF (Mental Level Factor): (SCF + KIF + INF + TCF + SKF + CTF + DVF)/10
PLF (Physical level Factor): (PCF + MCF + DXF + AGF + VHF)/10 

The speed effect in formula would be: XLF/5.  A little tiny effect.

This also impacts Saving throws(this made me happy when I realized the
potentials of a split STM).  Most are obvious.  What about System Shock?
Do I keep STM for system shock?

SO... Drum roll please... the proposed formulas:

MSD(Mental Speed): (DSC + INT - 20)/2 + LVF/10 + MLF/5
PSD(Physical SPD): (DSC + AGL - 20)/2 + LVF/10 + PLF/5

Look familiar at all? *SOB*


