"Re: BTR6A - the Speed Formula","A couple more thoughts on why STM should still go into speed...

I think the current perception formula is a good example of what ""feels
right"" and is playable.  Many LVFs go into perception to the point where
it is similar to STM in that high level characters are generally likely
to have higher perceptions.  In real life you would have a hard time
convincing me that a gourmet chef would be more likely to notice a
sniper on a distant roof than anyone else.  For that matter, you would
have a hard time convincing me that a great martial artist would. 
Still, I like the fact that higher ""level"" characters are more
perceptive.  Even though it is ridiculous to try to apply a broad
concept like ""level"" to real life, it is completely appropriate and
useful in a gaming system.

Consider the characters who are likely to have high STMs.  They will
generally be older more experienced NPCs or PCs who have run a lot. 
Either way they are people who have seen and experienced a lot.  I think
it is appropriate for them to be a little faster, even though I could
never dig up discrete data to prove it.  Sure there may be the
occasional librarian with a 300 INF and a 50 STM, but how likely is
Chuck to battle him to the death?  Come to that, how much would a couple
speed points help a librarian in a battle to the death against Chuck?

I would still propose putting STM (as is) into speed on top of the
currently proposed formulas.  I would suggest STM/10, but STM/20 is
probably easier for most others to swallow.  That would give at most 1-2
speed points to fairly high level characters in a system where you need
8-10 to make a big difference.
