"Re: BTR6A - the Speed Formula","Mark, 

Most of what you have been talking about is physical actions which are
mainly reflex based, and performed in a well understood setting (playing
volleyball, sparring in martial arts, etc.)  I actually agree with most
of what you have said in regard to these types of situations, but I
believe they are only a subset of the possible situations one encounters
in real life (or in BT for that matter).

In a reflex situation, muscle memory and natural ability are the most
important.  That is why AGL, LVF and Skill + Secondaries contribute the
large majority of speed points in any of the proposed formulas. 
However, many situations in BT are surprise, new or unique where
characters must figure out what is going on first, possibly even before
reflexes kick in.  (We have all heard many stories about very competant
martial artists getting nailed with a couple surprise punches before
their training kicks in).  When the situation is not fully understood,
that is when DSC and I still believe STM (at a lower level), are
critical.

Mark DesMarais wrote:
> 
> >Jeff
> >I could cite several counter examples...
> 
> And how long did this take? From the description, more than 2 seconds,
> right?  I can't emphasize this enough- the numbers we are talking about
> are less than 1 second intervals!!! Reaction time is completely washed
> out after a couple of seconds!!! (maybe even faster- I'm too weak to
> do the math)

I agree with what you said, but disagree with your conclusion. 
_Reaction_ time in BT is 2d6--0.4 to 2.4 seconds with 1.4 average.  That
is the amount of time (unmodified) somebody would stand around before
_starting_ an action.  In my experience, that is a pretty reasonable
timeframe.  In my example, the exec. finished completed everything in
about 2-3 seconds.  The others were still in their reaction phase when
he was done.  The fact that reaction time is washed out after a couple
of seconds does not mean that a couple of seconds is an insignificant
amount of time.  In fact, I have been arguing that those few seconds can
be critical.  But, I do not necessarily believe that _reaction_ speed
spills over into action speed.

Alex, Joe and I discussed the idea that it would be more realistic to
have separate reaction speeds (probably based on DSC, maybe STM) and
action speeds (probably based on Skill, LVF, Stats).  Even Alex (wisely
I think) balked at the idea of making speed that complex, so all of
these factors got rolled into one formula which is meant to roughly
model all the various situations a character might have to react to.

Finally, I think presets help (at least a little) to model reflexes.  In
a well-defined situation like volleyball or martial arts sparring, you
can make much more use of presets.  I imagine you have a preset to hit
the ball when it comes to you, and probably even know in advance where
you want to hit it.  Likewise, many martial arts teach block, kick, or
block, punch combinations so that the martial artist has a preset
response to an incoming attack.  You could argue that presets do not go
far enough, but they do significantly reduce the reaction time which is
the difference between DSC based and reflex based REactions.
