"BT:  Weapon Damages","This is from Geoff Hodge.  It is a pretty good note- I would love
people's comments on it.  I have two comments to think about:
(1) Weapons have one fundamental adavantage over hand-to-hand skills-
range.  Now, I suspect this may have been lost in the documentation- I
need to check- but for every foot in weapon length difference the
shorter weapon addsa count to it's weapon speed.  So- while knee is a
very effective high damage strike, it has a very short weapon length.
This makes it really slowe when facing, say a club or a staff.
(2) I think low speed weapons need to do more damage or high speed
weapons like fist and dagger might need to be a little slower.
Essentially I agree with Geoff.

Here is what Geoff said.....

Hi Alex,

  As you know, I abandoned Stephen's use of weapons through Desperate
Offense in favor of martial arts training because it seemed to be more
effective.  To put that impression to the test, I just reviewed the base

damages listed for crushing attacks (which covers unarmed combat and
most weapons that would be used in Desperate Offense attacks).

  In cases of armour or high PAB, higher damaging weapons will obviously

be more effective.  In the case of an unarmoured low PAB opponent though

unarmed combat looks superior to using weapons, which is not what I
would have expected.  Hopefully I am missing some rules somewhere that
balance things out.

  Below is a theoretical excercise listing, for each type of attack, the

average damage (assuming no skill or strength bonuses), the weapon
speed, the number of counts it would take to do 40 HTK damage (assuming
you hit each time), and the number of counts it would take to do 40 HTK
(assuming a Rank 6 attacker hitting each time at +4 dam), and finally
time to do 40 HTK assuming a total of +10 dam from primary, general,
secondary skills, STR bonus, etc):

               Avg Dam  Spd  ct/40HTK  ct/40HTK@+4  ct/40HTK@+10
Fist              4      4      40         20            11
Foot              6      6      40         24            15
Knee              8      4      20         13             9
Club              7      6      34         22            14
2 Hand Club       9     12      53         37            25
Quarterstaff     11     10      36         27            19

  This example discounts advantages of weapon length and difficulty
factor which would not tip the balance much.

  For an unskilled fighter, all weapons are roughly equal in their
ability to take down an opponent.  The difficulty mods might make Club
and Fist the top choices if you had no PCF.  With a decent PCF, Knee
looks like the bargain of the century.  Generally all attacks are in the

same ballpark.  I would have expected weapons to have an advantage as
long as they are not too tricky to use.

  Things change for the worse when you add some skill.  That not only
diminishes the effect of difficulty mods, but makes the quickest attacks

more favorable.  Two weapons, 2H club and Quarterstaff are left behind,
and only club is in the running with unarmed combat attacks.  At a
decent level of skill (+10 dam), Knee and Fist are definately the way to

go.  At this skill level you could drop unarmoured opponents with
unarmed combat almost twice as fast as you could with a 2H club or
Quarterstaff.  Stephen is not very strong, and only has rank 6 in most
martial arts skills, but he still racks up +14 points of damage on an
average punch, so these are not off-the-scale examples.

  I think the damages for unarmed combat attacks are too high (or maybe
the base times are too low).  Especially for Knee.  I'll let you take
your best Knee strike to my hand if you let me take my best shot at
yours with a good oak club ;-)

  Let me know what you think, and feel free to forward this to the BT
discussion group if you deem it worthwhile.




