> Fist              4       9      90
> Foot              6      10      66
> Knee              8      10      50
> Club              7       8      45
> 2 Hand Club       9      13      58
> Quarterstaff     11      10      36
> 

I agree that weapon length is a major factor in combat, and adding the
count per foot to short weapons does make the damage dealt per unit time
look much more reasonable.  Maybe some small tweaking of knee and 2H
club damage is all that is needed.

I also agree with Jim's observation that weapon length rules are very
seldom used, so this nice balance doesn't make it into play much.  Maybe
what is needed is an easier way to use these rules in combat.  My other
concern about weapon length is that all of these advantages are
cancelled (in fact they are reversed) if the opponent with the shorter
weapon closes.  I think it should be much easier to escape from a press
than it is to initiate a press.  From what I have seen, jamming is very
efffective, but also very hard to maintain.  People tend to stay at the
edge of their effective weapon range, and return to that range very
quickly and easily.

Weapon length, if enforced, would solve one problem, but I see a second
problem which it does not address--that is that damage bonuses from
strength and skill can be so large that the weapon is almost
incidental.  The difference between 4 and 6 points of average damage is
significant, but the difference between 24 and 26 points is not.  Chuck
Lee could kill you with a mushy banana almost as quickly as he could
kill you with a quarterstaff because his strength and skill bonuses are
much more important than his weapon.  Even among highly trained martial
artists I think weapons are a significant advantage.

I discovered a similar problem in my system and did a couple things that
did not solve the problem, but at least minimized it.  I doubled body
points and base weapon damage and left the level of effect bonus
(similar to skill bonus) and STR bonuses the same, so that they
contributed half as much relatively.  I also put a cap on max weapon
damage.  Each weapon has a max rolled damage.  STR and success/skill
bonuses cannot contribute more than the max rolled damage.  (Although
honestly I seldom enforce this rule since I don't like caps.  I am now
thinking that maybe you could get 1 extra point of damage per 2 levels
of effect beyond the max weapon damage.)  At any rate, I would like to
see the base damage of weapons increase relative to the strength and
skill bonuses in BT.
