There seems to be a consensus that weapon length rules, if enforced,
takes care of my original concern about fist being a faster way to drop
somebody that weapons.  However, this table assumes that the combat
range will be at the distance of the quarterstaff for the whole combat. 
If somebody with a short range weapon closes, the long weapon will be at
a disadvantage.  (No problem there, that's definately true).  The
problem is that if it is no easier to retreat than it is to press, then
a long weapon will be as likely to be a disadvantage as it is to be an
advantage.  That is why I really think it needs to either be very
difficult to close inside a weapon range or very easy to retreat back to
the longer weapon range.

> If closing were run as an action in and of itself then that, combined 
> with the length rules should give the longer weapon a significant
> edge.

I like the idea of making combat movement a separate action, because
people will be less likely to use it unless there is a real tactical
advantage.  It would not really give an advantage to longer weapons
because as long as the first opponent spent an action and successfully
closed, the second opponent would have to spend an action to retreat
back to his effective range.  Or did you mean make press an action but
retreat free?  That would be a pretty simple mechanism, and would
certainly give the advantage to longer weapons.

At the risk of sounding like a broken record.  I still think even a club
does significantly more base damage than a punch, or probably even a
kick.  (And maybe even the dreaded Death Knee).  If somebody took a
punch at me I would be worried about a broken nose.  If somebody took a
swing at me with a club, I would worry about getting my skull caved in.

What level of skill does a brown belt or black belt have in BT? 
Straight rank 6's?  Straight 4's?  Lets be conservative.  With 4's in
punch, G:, and secondaries, a martial artist would be +5 from skill.  Do
you martial artists who were in that range think it would be easier to
break someone's arm with your skilled punch or with your unskilled club
swing?

I don't know how the number of joules of force was calculated, but if it
was just F=MA, that may be an oversimplification.  Fists, knees and feet
are compressable and will reabsorb some of the energy they impart.  A
solid wood or metal club will absorb much less of the energy, so more
will be transferred to the target.


