I agree that combat happens much too quickly in BT (and all ""real time""
systems I have come across).  The idea of rounds in D&D is explained
somewhere as the time it takes for a good target to open up, but that
mechanism obviously causes another series of problems itself.

Most players I have seen, even in systems that reward tactics, default
to swing-swing-swing-swing.  Because of woundedness mods, it is usually
advantageous to rack up as much damage on your opponent as quickly as
you can.  The advantage of defending yourself is not significant enough
(or at least it does not appear that way to many players) for them to
change tactics.

For the sake of game theory discussion, here are a couple rough ideas on
how to maybe model hand to hand combat more realistically:

1) Use a mechanism that would allow people to create/find targets as a
function of skill.  A rank 1 puncher could, say, find one target every
10 seconds while a rank 8 puncher could find 8 targets.  Feint, combat
perception and combat movement could be used to increase the number of
targets per unit time while defense could be used to decrease them.

OR

2) Make defense much more powerful so that it is very difficult to score
a solid hit on someone without catching them reacting.  Then people
might wait for the other guy to strike first in order to catch him
reacting.  Of course feint and maybe combat movement could be altered to
make them more important in drawing out that first punch or unnecessary
block.  This could also explain why black belts tend to spend so much
time with footwork and feinting--since they react so quickly they have
to wait until their opponent really botches a reaction roll to give them
time to strike while he is reacting.  It would also explain why
competant black belts often get beat up when they get jumped from
surprise.

