"Re: BT: Endurance","     It seems to me that Alex and Pookie are discussing two different 
     things.  One is Endurance, the other is Recovery.  
     
     I think Pookie's observation that Endurance is related to Skill is 
     completely accurate and intuitively obvious.  Someone who is in great 
     shape, but has never ridden a horse, will not endure as long as a 
     trained rider - even if the rider is generally out of shape.  The 
     rider's training has built 'extra' endurance in the specific group of 
     muscles that riding requires.  
     
     That addresses the first half of the equation:  Namely, ""How soon does 
     one get exhausted?""  I think that this aspect can be easily 
     incorporated into the present system by increasing Endurance 
     proportionally to your Skill.  
     
     However, the second half of the equation, then, is:  ""Once you are 
     exhausted, how long does it take to recover?""  I am not an expert in 
     the field of physical exhaustion; the research I have done is in the 
     area of sleep deprivation.  Some of what is relevent there may apply 
     here.  
     
     In the area of sleep, we can distinguish three major states:  active 
     (awake), resting (maintain), and sleep (recovery).  It occurs for most 
     people that there is a certain amount of 'required' sleep necessary, 
     regardless of the amount of rest.  Staying Active beyond this required 
     amount builds up a 'sleep deficit'.  Resting does not increase the 
     sleep deficit, but it doesn't relieve it, either.  
     
     Staying Active while sleep deprived is possible, but comes with a cost 
     above and beyond the extra recovery time.  I guess you would say it 
     degrades Mental Awareness, Mental Agility, Physical Agility (and 
     perhaps others).  Even so, at some point, the body will refuse to stay 
     active, and essentially will knock you out to go into recovery.  
     
     The important part here is:  that once the body goes into recovery 
     (sleep), it tends to stay there until the job is done (the deficit has 
     been paid for).  This is so even if we are experientially unaware of 
     our level of deprivation.  In sleep trials using rooms without time 
     cues, normal, everyday Americans sleep, on average, 12 hours their 
     first night of the study (afterwards scaling back to about 8 
     hours/night).  
     
     What I think is most important to model here, is the folk wisdom - ""I 
     wasn't tired until I set down a spell.""  I don't think it's so 
     important to decide how long before you're 'back to normal' - I think 
     it's important to decide how long you are incapacitated during 
     recovery.  And I do mean incapacitated.  If someone has not run in a 
     long while, and then they decide to run 3 or 4 miles, their body may 
     support them at the time.  But the next day, they will hardly be able 
     to walk.  
     
     If it were my task to model this phenomenon, instead of modeling 
     Extreme Exhaustion, as it were, I'd model in Deprivation as negative 
     Endurance (0 would be 'exhausted').  This would mean that someone with 
     a high level of Endurance in a particular skill would take longer to 
     go 'negative' - before they take hits to their MAW,MDX,PDX, etc. - but 
     that they'd still have to take the time being incapacitated when they 
     eventually went into recovery (slept).  
     
     Oh, well, that's my take on the matter.  
     
     [ron]
     


