"BT: Endurance questions","This post responds up to Pookie's post of January 6th, 12:25 pm.

I am not going to try to copy people's texts.  I am going to try to be as
brief as possible- I don't have time and neither I am sure, do you!  So.....

First off- what Jim said about the studies of endurance.  BT is designed to
reflect that:
END(endurance) = oxygen intake energy, comes back within minutes....
EXT(exhaustion) = other supplies of energy, reserves, comes back in hours
and days, requires rest
MEXT(meta-exhaustion) = body damage, depleting the body for energy, comes
back in days, requires rest

I am not going to get rid of EXT and MEXT as per Mark's suggestion because
they are game balancers.  However, most of the time character's don't have
to worry about them.

I agree with people that- and it seems unanimous that it is true:-) - that
the ENDURANCE pools go up much slower than the way we model and rank in
skill allows the user to be more and more efficient at the skill.  I just
haven't come up with a playable model.  Pools that grow with Level factors
is easy.  Any brilliant ideas?

Pook wrote:
>Let us use the example of Dashing (10PEX/min) and ignore meta-exhaustion
>for now:

It is important to remember that although as a short hand we talk about
walking taking 6 EXT per hour, it really takes 1 END a minute, and DASHING
takes 1 END every 3 counts.  This is important because I don't think Sigmund
can actually DASH for 43 minutes straight.    Sigmund would run out of END
in about 4 minutes- and then have to rest to recover.  In two or three
minutes he could start again.  END is always the first thing.

>Joe, being a human, gets about (2+4+8+8+4*8) 54 PEX back for a normal
>eight hour night of sleep.  As I understand it you can't get value for more
>than eight hours of sleep in a night but I was fuzzy on that

You can sleep as long as you want.   I have occasionally used GM fiat to
dictate that you can't sleep for 24 hours ""because you are not tired
anymore"" (mostly mages trying to do the cast everything for ten minutes,
sleep for ten hours, cast everything for ten minutes rule abuse...:-)).

Your first hour of sleep is light sleep and gives you 2 EXT, 0 MEXT
Your second hour of sleep is medium sleep and gives you 4 EXT, 0 MEXT
All following hours of sleep are deep sleep and give you 8 EXT, 0.5 MEXT

I agree with Peter and Mark and others  that character's should be able to
""save"" endurance by matching the slower members of the party, etc. AND
choose whether they are saving energy or going for ""speed"".   My only
question- is there a simply way to model that without excessive bookkeeping?

IN RESPONSE to POOK's suggestion:

We cannot ditch Meta-exhaustion.  However I can kick it up to the design
level and only trot it out to reign in characters that are trying to not
sleep for two months or something......

I don't like using the HTK rules because of the fact that there are more
variables in endurance recovery like rest.....
Also having it be three pools makes it easy to track- you don't have to know
which day you are on or how many you have already healed in this category,
etc.  You know what you have to do to recover  a MEXT, EXT or an END.  AND
the mechanism of EXT coming off the top of end models what seems to happen
in real life nicely.    I.e. you recover to an extant, and then use a bunch
of endurance, recover to a slightly lesser extant, use a bunch of endurance
etc.....

I also like Pookie's formula/chart for using crits to reduce endurance cost.
I have no problem with that except I would modify it as I mention in my
earlier post:

> Levels Of Critical Endurance

> 0 x2/3
> 1 x1/2
> 2 x2/5
> 3 x1/3
> 4 x2/7
> 5 x1/4
> ...


Okay folks- go wild- tell me what you think.....







