"Re: BT: Re: Endurance","     I'm right on board with regard to The Endurance Question.  I agree 
     that basing it on criticals is appropriate and elegant.  
     
     However, I'd like to weigh in on the Recovery Question (230lbs.).  
     Although it may be easier to play, I'd like to propose that Physical 
     and Mental Recovery are different and should be calculated separately.  
     I could get how HTK recovery stages of 25% (seconds, minutes, days, 
     weeks) is appropriate for Physical Recovery.  I'm not so sure it is 
     best modelled that way for Mental Recovery.  
     
     Alex is right when he says that you enter deep sleep a couple hours 
     after head hits pillow.  However, that is not the case with an 
     'exhausted' person.  The plunge into deep sleep is much faster.  The 
     body works directly on deep sleep to completely make up the deficit.  
     Also, it is hard to imagine what Mental Recovery would still be needed 
     after any 12-hour sleep.  To say that days later you are still not 
     Recovered is contrary even to subjective experience.  
     
     I propose that all Mental Recovery be complete within one 'sleep' 
     session, and that sleep sessions generally last 8-12 hours, or, at the 
     outside - 20 hours.  
     
     Now this is not to say that Mental Exhaustion might not cause some 
     attendant Physical Exhaustion, and that it may take days to recover 
     from the aforesaid Physical Exhaustion.  Indeed, I think this is 
     closer to reality.  Days after one's all-nighter, it's not what you've 
     done to your Mind that you're recovering from, it's what you've done 
     to your body.  
     
     So unless it's already in there, I propose that Mental Exhaustion 
     provide hits to Physical Agility etc., and that Mental Meta-Exhaustion 
     reduce your physical well-being, as well.  
     
     [ron]
     
