Appendix 2- ON CRITICALS

>The only caveat with this is that it seems ambiguous to me what a
>0 level of critical means.

Okay.  This is, I think, a nomenclature problem.   It is axiomatic to most
RPGs and realism simulations  that there is a chance for particularly good
successes.  Out of this, the concept of ""criticals"" or ""very good success""
comes.

In BT the distinctions were made along these breakpoints:

SN = Success number = number you need to roll to succeed in the skill
(RANK*10 + LVF + MODs)

CSN = Critical Success Number = 1/4 of your success number.

Under the success number:  Normal Success  skill successfully applied,
half-damage
Under half the SN:         Crit Level 0        full-damage
Under quarter the SN(CSK): Crit Level 1        1.5* damage
Under CSN-10:              Crit Level 2        2* damage
Under CSN-20:              Crit Level 3        2.5* damage
Under CSN-30:              Crit Level 4        3* damage etc.

To get the damage modifier of a crit, divide the crit level by 2 and add 1.
That is the
damage multiplier.

The crit level is the amount  (CSN - number rolled)/10 + 1

Crit level 0 is just the name of the level.  It counts as a single level of
critical.

>Lets say that I punch and for some reason
>I want to reduce my endurance as well as upping my damage.  I
>roll a level 2 critical.  Now what can I do?  Can I allocate 2 levels to
>damage and 0 levels to reducing endurance?


Yes- but 0 levels of critical buy you nothing. Example:
SN=100 so CSN=25.
I roll a 66.  Thai s a normal success.  No levels of critical.
I roll a43.  That is a crit level 0.  It is one level of critical to apply
to whatever I want.
I roll a 22.  That is a crit level 1.  It is two levels of critical to play
with.  I could put one to Endurance(2/3 cost) and one to damage(full
damage).
I roll a 13.  That is a crit level 2.  It is three levels of endurance to
play with.  I could put two to damage(1.5 times damage) and one to
endurance(2/3 cost).

