Good question.  After reading all these posts I have the same question.:-)
Mark has an answer!:-)

However, OPINION ALERT:
In REAL LIFE(TM) Kata shape the way a person fights and give the person a
benefit in how smoothly and quickly a person can perform those actions in
sequence.  The real benefit- beside the practice in the individual skills
used in the Kata - is that one gets quicker and quicker and smoother and
smoother at moving between actions and executing transitions.   This
describes one type of Kata or Form.  Other forms are designed solely to
train people in the included skills and some to enhance stats and
endurance...  The Kata skill would refer to the type I first mentioned...

That said....

I think they are worth modeling.  The only ""transition"" mechanism in BARDIC
TALES is initiative.  There are three ways to make actions flow together
faster:
(1) Use a quickstrike skill for all your actions.  (Unlikely at best)

(2) Instant Attack all your actions.  This works but..... your first action
is at -40, your second at -60 and every one thereafter is at -60.  But the
beauty is you roll a 0 on your initiative roll and can use your whole SPD as
ACTION points.  The breakdown is that your perceptions are cut in half and
you are locked in to what you said you would do.  If you try to break the
chain you need to re-roll initiative as if surprised!!!( +12 to INIT)

(3) You could use pre-sets.  Pre-sets are a declared series of actions.  It
allows you to roll 2d6/2 for initiative instead of 2d6.   It is as Instant
Attack except that you roll as if you missed your last action(+4 INIT)
instead of being surprised if you break the chain.

What I did to start was I originally conceived Kata's as a pre-determined
series of  Instant Attacks,with it giving bonuses like a support skill(3%per
RANK) and 1 INIT point per RANK in Kata.    The Kata would be broken in to
series of 2-6 action sequences that were very pre-determined.  You had to
note what support skills you were using, which hex you were acting into, and
whether the action was low, high, or mid-level.  For every sequence you had
beyond the first in a single Kata you would take a -5% to the Kata's
difficulty factor.

Now- what that created was a thing that, as Jim has noted, a low-level
character could not use.  It only became useful when the characters chances
were high enough to overcome the Instant Attack Mods.  This models real life
I think - as any of you who have studied martial arts can attest- Kata are
not useful in practical fighting until you are really good.  Then many
high-level practitioners swear by them!

So that is the thought behind Kata.  I still think that this method models
the way Kata are most closely and keeps them form being too useful- if we
swapped the Instant Attacks into Pre-sets for instance a Kata is a great
support skill to have!!!!

Now- what I have done is run some numbers and the INIT bonus is probably too
gross as Pookie says below.  I would probably have it add 3% per RANK,  SPD
AND DAM like a secondary skill(I.e. (RANK-2)/2  instead of RANK)  to all
actions in the KATA.

PROPOSAL:  Have Kata be a support skill(I.e. above and beyond the
secondaries and generals) to all skills in its umbrella.  It will add 3% per
RANK to-hit, and  (RANK-2)/2  to SPD and DAM to all of its skills.  All the
Skills would be Instant Attacks, they would be organized into sequences of
2-5 actions with reactions in between.  The Kata would have to be activated
with a successful roll, though no crit would be possible as in all support
skills.   Every sequence written into a Kata beyond the first would add -10%
to the activation roll of the Kata.

