          ON CRITICALS
>The only caveat with this is that it seems ambiguous to me what a
>0 level of critical means.
Okay.  This is, I think, a nomenclature problem. It is axiomatic to most
RPGs and realism simulations that there is a chance for particularly good
successes.  Out of this, the concept of ""criticals"" or ""success levels""
comes.
In BT the distinctions are now made along these breakpoints:

SN = Success number = number you need to roll to succeed in the skill
(RANK*10 + LVF + MODs, generated by final success chance...)
CSN = Critical Success Number = 1/4 of your SN.
SL = Success Level

Under the success number:  SL 1  skill applied,half-damage
Under half the SN:         SL 2        full-damage
Under quarter the SN(CSN): SL 3        1.5* damage
Under CSN-10:              SL 4        2* damage
Under CSN-20:              SL 5        2.5* damage
Under CSN-30:              SL 6        3* damage etc.

To get the damage modifier of a hit, divide the SL by 2.  That is the damage
multiplier.  This assumes you are using your SLs for damage/effect.  You
could also use them for reducing END cost, or increasing effect duration, or
effect control, or some other things I am sure you will all think of....

The SL is the amount {(CSN - number rolled)/10 + 3 [rounded down]} for all
successes below SL 2.

>Lets say that I punch and for some reason
>I want to reduce my endurance as well as upping my damage.  I
>roll a SL 2.  Now what can I do?  Can I allocate 2 levels to
>damage and 0 levels to reducing endurance?
Yes- Though, as is intuitively obvious(*GRIN*) 0 levels will get you no
result. :-) Example:
SN=100 so CSN=25.
I roll a 66.  This is a SL 1. One level of success.
I roll a 43.  That is a SL 2.  It is two levels of success to apply
to whatever I want.
I roll a 22.  That is a SL 3.  It is three levels of success to play
with.  I could put one to Endurance(2/3 cost) and two to damage(full
damage).
I roll a 13.  That is a SL 2.  It is three levels of endurance to
play with.  I could put two to damage(1.5 times damage) and one to
endurance(2/3 cost).

--- --- ---
          ON ENDURANCE
In this conversation Physical and Mental Endurances are equivalent.
Therefore we refer to END and EXT- but these refer to both Physical
Endurance(END) and Mental Endurance(MEN).  Likewise for exhaustion.
Physical and Mental endurance and exhaustion are recovered simultaneously
and identically.
Currently END, EXT, and M-EXT (Endurance, Exhaustion, and Meta-Exhaustion)
use the idea that Endurance is like a pool of energy that you have a certain
amount of and that increases as one becomes more skilled.  Actions use up
Endurance like fuel.
ENDURANCE:  Basic ""fuel unit"".
It returns after use at 1 per ten counts... usually all back in 3-5 minutes.
Resting or sleeping doubles the return rate.
EXHAUSTION: EXT comes off the top of END at a rate of 1 per 10 END expended.
It returns at 1 per two hours of rest, 2 per hour of light sleep, 4 per hour
of medium sleep, and 8 per hour of full deep sleep.  Meals can also restore
1-3 EXT three times a day.  Meditation is as medium sleep.
META-EXHAUSTION: M-EXT comes off END as well.  One accumulates one M-EXT for
every 10 EXT one accumulates.
It returns at a rate of: 1 per 4 hours of complete rest(not doing any
activity- not expending more than 20 endurance in an hour), 1 per 2 hours of
deep sleep(Deep sleep is usually achieved in the third hour of sleep)
Your first hour of sleep is light sleep and gives you 2 EXT, .25 M-EXT
Your second hour of sleep is medium sleep and gives you 4 EXT,.25 M-EXT
All following hours of sleep are deep sleep and give you 8 EXT,.5 M-EXT

If a character is moving or acting at some percentage of full effort
(travelling with slower companions, taking their time, only punching white
belts) they only expend that percentage of the END cost of the action.  I.e.
if a character has a walk of 1.4 and the group is moving at .7, she only
expends 50% of the END cost for that type of movement.
Levels of critical can be used to decrease endurance cost just like they can
be used to increase damage.  The following table describes the effect:
     Effect of Success Levels on Endurance
1 x2/3
2 x1/2
3 x2/5
4 x1/3
5 x2/7
6 x1/4
...
NOTE: In most cases you need to put at least one success level in a roll to
effect or there will be 0 effect.  :-)  So usually you would never put all
your success levels towards reducing endurance.
Optional Rule: whenever the rules call for recovering 1 ENDURANCE or
EXHAUSTION it is read as 1% of the character's END or EXT.  The amount of
END or EXT recovered is tallied and then the modifier is applied.
I.e. if a character recovers 54 points over night, then that is translated
to 54% of total and rounded up to the nearest integer.
This rule will probably be used by characters with ENDURANCES over 100...
:-)
--- --- ---
          ON SPEED
Speed Points(SPD) => the number generated by the character's PSPD/MSPD stat,
plus the LVF/10, plus the RANK modifiers: primary(RANK-2),
secondaries([RANK-2]/2), and general([RANK-2]/2), plus any SPECIAL
POINTS(Support skills like Quickstrike, Environmental variables)
Initiative points(INIT) => the number subtracted from the characters
initiative roll.  Usually half the speed points, rounded up. Can be added to
directly by SUPPORT SKILLS like Kata.
Action Points(ACT) => the points used to speed up actions, perform passive
actions or set-up.  Usually half the speed points, rounded down. Can be
added to directly by some SUPPORT SKILLS like Quickdraw
Negative initiative would turn into ACT on a 1 per 1 basis.
Quickstrike would generate 1 SPD per RANK.    Kata would generate 1 INIT per
RANK.  A specific Quickdraw skill would generate 1 ACT per RANK.
To buy 1 ACT => 10% to-hit or 3 points of damage(only for muscle-power
weapons) or 1 negative initiative
One ACT will buy you:  2%-to-hit or 1/3 DAM or 1 count off of a passive
action (perception(8 counts), support skill initiation(usually 8 counts),
general skill activation(usually 8 counts, Kata is 4 counts), etc.) So 8
ACTION points will buy you a full passive perception or general skill
activation.
--- --- ---
          ON SETUP
Set-up in real counts will give you 5% per count and is limited to:
(1) 10 + KIF/2 counts of set-up AND
(2) a maximum value equal to  (RANK*10+LVF)- or the default value(saves,
MAP, etc.)- of the skill being set-up for.
Do not include secondaries or generals in set-up base chance and do not
include the difficulty of the skill.  Only include the RAW SUCCESS CHANCE:
RANK*10 + LVF.  This is because the more difficult actions are where set-up
is really needed and IMO makes the most difference in real-life.
The set-up skill allows you to double the set-up bonus per count for the
first RANK counts of set-up.

--- --- ---
          ON SUPPORT SKILLS
You may no longer roll against support skills.  They give their
3% per rank or 1 SPD point per rank and that is it.  This change alleviates
two problems:
(1) People have been getting high bonuses because they are criticalling
their support skill rolls.  This is often because of level factor and other
bonuses that already give to the primary skill, so they are redundant
bonuses.
(2) This change reduces the number of rolls people have to make in play.
Your quickstrike just adds Rank in SPD points to your action.  Period!  Your
florentine gives you 3% per rank- period.  No need to do another roll- no
need to recalculate for levels of success, etc.
This is a blessing for people with low ranks because it means you don't fail
your roll either- you always get 6% for your rank 2 support skill!:-)
Support skills can go above the negative modifier for a skill. (I.e. a RANK
15 Florentine character gets +45% and the minus is only minus 40%.  This
person is 5% better florentining than not florentining.)
You may use as many support skills as applicable skills you are using.  If
you have unused support skills they may be used as secondaries.

Whenever it is not stated what the contribution of a secondary, support or
general skill  is- but you know it makes a contribution- you can assume it
contributes:
3% per RANK to-hit
(RANK - 2)/2 to SPD
(RANK - 2)/2 to DAM
Note that some support skills do not contribute to-hit or def: Quickstrike,
Quickdraw
Some do not contribute to SPD: Called Shot, Feint, Set-Up, Evasion,  Armor
Wearing, Great Blow
Some do not contribute to  DAM: Called Shot, Quick Strike, Quick Draw,
Feint, Parry, Set-up. Evasion, Armor Wearing, Instant Attack, Great Blow
ON INSTANT ATTACK
Instant attacks are attacks in which the initiative roll is
automatically adjusted to 0.  It is declared at a reaction, a normal attack
is launched and then the next attack begins the sequence with an INIT roll
of 0 .  The penalties are -40 for the first instant attack, -50 for the next
one, and -60 for all following instant attacks.  As with pre-sets the
actions must be declared at the reaction.  Each action must be specifically
declared.  One can declare up to (RANK + DRIVE/3) actions.  Recurring loops
are possible.  For instance: I block high and then I hit him again and again
and again and don't stop till he is dead......

ON KI FOCUS
Ki Focus is a separate skill that has no speed effects.  It takes
10 counts to do, and is good for one action.  It allows the user to pour
KI(MEN) into damage and to-hit chance.  The to-hit bonus for this will also
be limited to the raw SC=> (RANK*10+LVF) or the max damage of the attack.
Adds RANK/4 to-hit or RANK/8 in damage per MEN used.
It is also a prerequisite for several ""monkish"" skills: Body Control, Iron
Skin, Reduce Exhaustion.
ON Mage Trance, Battle Trance, Ki Trance etc.
These also cannot be criticalled- They will make perceptions and all
applicable skills easier (15% + 3% per rank).  When a trance is induced a
specific perception is activated.  You must roll to enter a trance.  It
takes 30 counts, and no crit effects can be used for to-hit modification.
The pluses here are also limited to the raw success chance of the primary
skill being modified.
ON Katas
Have Kata be a support skill(I.e. above and beyond the secondaries and
generals) to all skills in its umbrella.  It will add 3% per RANK to-hit,
and RANK in INIT to all of its skills.  All the Skills would be Instant
Attacks, they would be organized into sequences of 2-5 actions with
reactions in between.  One could enter or leave a sequence at the reactions
in-between and those reactions re-set the Instant Attacks. The Kata would
have to be activated  with a successful roll, though no crit would be
possible as in all support skills.   Every sequence written into a Kata
beyond the first would add -10% to the activation roll of the Kata. Breaking
the Kata at a non-reaction carries a +8 penalty. (double the penalty for
missing a normal action.)
Summary:
Kata are composed of a number of sequences.
Each sequence has 2-5 actions.
Each sequence is treated as a series of instant attacks.
The first action of a sequence is a normal attack.
Breakout can occur between sequences, or with a penalty.
Katas are 'simple activation' skills, with no crit potential.
Kata skills add 3% per rank to all actions in the Kata.
Example:
Bob the Paladin decided he wants to use his ""squish 'em, gish 'em, turn 'em""
Kata.
(1)He rolls a reaction.
He acts in 2 counts.
(2)When his action comes he says 'I activate ""squish 'em, gish 'em, turn
'em"" '.  He rolls his Kata skill as a Primary and succeeds.  He declares
what sequence he will use(this Kata only has one) and that he will start
right into the Kata. (SEE OPTION 2 BELOW)
It takes him 4 counts to do this. We are now on count 6.
(3)He takes the first action of the Kata without rolling intuitive.  He
automatically gets a zero and starts the action on count six.  He gets all
his SPD as ACT points and takes a -40(modified by RANK*3 in the KATA).  It
takes him 2 counts after ACT mods to squish.
(4) At count 8 he starts right into gishing.  It takes him 2 counts after
ACT mods and he takes a -50(modified by RANK*3 in the KATA).
(5)At count 10 he starts a turn.  It takes him five counts after ACT mods
and he is at a -60(modified by RANK*3 in the KATA).
(6)At count 15 the turn goes off and he rolls a reaction roll 3 seconds
after deciding to go into the Kata.
OPTION 2: After successfully rolling KATA, you can roll a reaction and then
act so that the first action of the Kata isn't at -40, it is as a normal
action, and the second action is the first instant attack.

