--- --- ---
          ON CRITICALS/SUCCESS LEVELS

It is axiomatic to most RPGs and realism simulations that there is a chance
for particularly good successes.  Out of this, the concept of ""criticals"" or
""success levels"" comes.
In BT the distinctions are now made along these breakpoints:

SN = Success number = number you need to roll to succeed in the skill
(RANK*10 + LVF + MODs, generated by final success chance...)

CSN = Critical Success Number = 1/4 of your SN.

SL = Success Level

NOTE: In these discussions we will speak about damage and effect
interchangeably.  Mostly this is an artifact of the skill system growing out
of a gaming system that focused on modeling weapon effects.  However the
pluses to Damage(DAM), and the multipliers for effect are both modeling the
same area.  For purposes of weapons effect is damage and for purposes of
non-weapon skills DAM is the same as effect.

     Effect of Success Levels on Effect
Under the success number:  SL 1  skill applied,half-effect
Under half the SN:         SL 2        full-effect
Under quarter the SN(CSN): SL 3        1.5* effect
Under CSN-10:              SL 4        2* effect
Under CSN-20:              SL 5        2.5* effect
Under CSN-30:              SL 6        3* effect etc.

To get the damage modifier of a hit, divide the SL by 2.  That is the effect
multiplier.  This assumes you are using your SLs for effect.  You could also
use them for reducing END cost(see Endurance section for success level
effect on Endurance), or increasing effect duration(mechanism to be
determined), or effect control(mechanism to be determined), or some other
things I am sure you will all think of....

NOTE: It is advisable to always put at least one level of success into
effect/damage or you will have no effect!:-)(Although I can see in a
practice fight you might put all your success levels into endurance cost or
showmanship or something...)

     Effect of Success Levels on Endurance
1 x2/3
2 x1/2
3 x2/5
4 x1/3
5 x2/7
6 x1/4
...
     Effect of Success Levels on ACT/INIT points
SL ACT or INIT
1  +3      +1
2  +6      +3
3  +9      +5
4  +12     +6
5  +15     +7
6  +18     +9

NOTE:  ACT points from SL(SL*3) go toward the action (I.e. the character is
so successful and smooth with the action they can do it faster...).
INIT points from SL(SL*1.5, round down) go towards the reaction IMMEDIATELY
after the action (I.e. the character is so much smoother with the action
they can transition into the next action better.
...
The SL is the amount {(CSN - number rolled)/10 + 3 [rounded down]} for all
successes below SL 2.
Example:
SN=100 so CSN=25.
I roll a 66.  This is a SL 1. One level of success.
*
I roll a 43.  That is a SL 2.  It is two levels of success to apply
to whatever I want.  One could apply both levels to effect(full damage), OR
one level to effect(1/2 damage) and one level to reducing endurance(2/3
endurance cost).
*
I roll a 22.  That is a SL 3.  It is three levels of success to play
with.
I could put one to Endurance(2/3 cost) and two to effect(full
damage)
or all three to effect(1.5*damage)
or one to ACT points(3 points), one to Endurance(2/3 cost), and one to
Effect(.5*damage).
*
I roll a 13.  That is a SL 4.  It is four levels of success to
play with.  I could put three to effect(1.5*damage) and one to
endurance(2/3 cost), or one to effect(half damage) and three to
endurance(2/5 cost), etc.

--- --- ---
          ON ENDURANCE

In this conversation Physical and Mental Endurances are equivalent.
Therefore we refer to END and EXT- but these refer to both Physical
Endurance(END) and Mental Endurance(MEN).  Likewise for exhaustion.
Physical and Mental endurance and exhaustion are recovered simultaneously
and identically.

Currently END, EXT, and M-EXT (Endurance, Exhaustion, and Meta-Exhaustion)
use the idea that Endurance is like a pool of energy that you have a certain
amount of and that increases as one becomes more skilled.  Actions use up
Endurance like fuel.

ENDURANCE:  Basic ""fuel unit"".
It returns after use at 1 per ten counts... usually all back in 3-5 minutes.
Resting or sleeping doubles the return rate.

EXHAUSTION: EXT comes off the top of END at a rate of 1 per 10 END expended.
It returns at 1 per two hours of rest, 2 per hour of light sleep, 4 per hour
of medium sleep, and 8 per hour of full deep sleep.  Meals can also restore
1-3 EXT three times a day.  Meditation is as medium sleep.

META-EXHAUSTION: M-EXT comes off END as well.  One accumulates one M-EXT for
every 10 EXT one accumulates.
It returns at a rate of: 1 per 4 hours of complete rest(not doing any
activity- not expending more than 20 endurance in an hour), 1 per 2 hours of
deep sleep(Deep sleep is usually achieved in the third hour of sleep)

Your first hour of sleep is light sleep and gives you 2 EXT, .25 M-EXT
Your second hour of sleep is medium sleep and gives you 4 EXT,.25 M-EXT
All following hours of sleep are deep sleep and give you 8 EXT,.5 M-EXT

If a character is moving or acting at some percentage of full effort
(travelling with slower companions, taking their time, only punching white
belts) they only expend that percentage of the END cost of the action.  I.e.
if a character has a walk of 1.4 and the group is moving at .7, she only
expends 50% of the END cost for that type of movement.

Levels of critical can be used to decrease endurance cost just like they can
be used to increase damage.  The following table describes the effect:
     Effect of Success Levels on Endurance
1 x2/3
2 x1/2
3 x2/5
4 x1/3
5 x2/7
6 x1/4
...
NOTE: In most cases you need to put at least one success level in a roll to
effect or there will be 0 effect.  :-)  So usually you would never put all
your success levels towards reducing endurance.

Optional Rule: whenever the rules call for recovering 1 ENDURANCE,
EXHAUSTION, or META-EXHAUSTION it is read as 1% of the character's
endurance.  The amount of endurance recovered is tallied and then the
modifier is applied.

I.e. if a character recovers 54 points over night, then that is translated
to 54% of total and rounded up to the nearest integer.

This rule will probably be used by characters with ENDURANCES over 100...
:-)

--- --- ---
          ON TIME
Managing flow of actions, sequencing of occurrences and time-flow in Bardic
Tale is modeled by breaking time up into discrete units called counts.  Each
count is the equivalent of a fifth of a second.

Then there is a system called ""initiative"" that manages when a character
acts and reacts in counts.  This is based on a series of variables including
the primary stats AGL, DSC, and INT; the secondary stats of Physical
Speed(PSPD) or Mental Speed(MSPD); the Total Level Factor of the
character(TLF); the Physical Level Factor(PLF) or Mental Level Factor(MLF),
and the Level Factor of the skill being used in the action.  This
""initiative"" also includes the person's RANK in the skill about to be used,
and on the similar skills supporting it, the character's physical
well-being, mental state, and other situational modifiers.  These variables
are all bundled together under a single number called SPD.

To simulate the variability of our interface with the world, the
""initiative"" is generated by rolling two 6-sided dice and adding them
together and then modifying them by SPD/2(rounded up).  The resultant number
is the number of counts a character must wait until they can start an
action.  This is their ""reaction time"" in counts.

During the course of a combat or specific interaction, the GM will walk
through time count by count. In each count there is an action phase and a
reaction phase.   When a person ""rolls initiative"" and generates a number,
that number is the number of counts the person takes to ""react"" to their
environment and start an action.  If the number is negative(due to
modifiers) then it is declared as zero counts.  This means that the person
can declare what action they are starting immediately and it will start in
the action phase of the next count.  All the negative initiative(plus
SPD/2[rounded down]) gets turned into ACTION POINTS, which can be used to
speed up the time it actually takes to do the action.

Then each action has a speed assigned to it.  This is called
WeaponSpeed(WSD- this is another layover from the time when all skills were
modeling combat!).  This speed is also a measure of the ""counts"" it takes to
perform the action.   So once the person is finished reacting they would
confirm which action they were taking during the action phase of that count.
That would be the first count of the action.  When they reach the action
phase of the count which is modified WSD counts later they would roll their
skill roll and the action would take place.

Some skill options that change this slightly are pre-sets and instant
attacks.  The only difference is that when using a pre-set you roll 2d6/2
instead of 2d6 for the reaction variation.  In an instant attack you proceed
as if you had ROLLED a 0[normally impossible] on your 2d6/2 pre-set roll.

SPEED mechanics are explained in more detail below.

--- --- ---
          ON SPEED

Speed Points(SPD) => the number generated by the character's PSPD/MSPD stat,
plus the LVF/10, plus the RANK modifiers: primary(RANK-2),
secondaries([RANK-2]/2), and general([RANK-2]/2), plus any SPECIAL
POINTS(Support skills like Quickstrike, Environmental variables, Physical
and Mental state of the character)

Initiative points(INIT) => the number subtracted from the characters
initiative roll.  It is equal to half the speed points, rounded up. Is added
to directly by some SUPPORT SKILLS like Kata.

Action Points(ACT) => the points used to speed up actions, perform passive
actions or add to-hit.  It is equal to half the speed points, rounded down.
Is added to directly by some SUPPORT SKILLS like Quickdraw

Negative initiative turns into ACT on a 1 per 1 basis.

Quickstrike generates 1 SPD per RANK.    Kata generates 1 INIT per RANK.  A
specific Quickdraw skill generates 1 ACT per RANK.

To buy 1 ACT => 10% to-hit or 3 points of damage(only for muscle-powered
weapons) or 1 negative initiative

One ACT will buy you:  2%-to-hit or 1/3 DAM or 1 count off of a passive
action (perception[8 counts], support skill initiation[usually 8 counts],
general skill activation[usually 8 counts, Kata{not a general skill but a
support skill that required activation} is 4 counts], etc.)
So 8 ACTION points will buy you a full passive perception or general skill
activation.

--- --- ---
          ON SETUP

Set-up in real counts will give you 5% per count and is limited to:

(1) 10 + KIF/2 counts of set-up AND

(2) a maximum value equal to  (RANK*10+LVF)- or the default value(saves,
MAP, etc.)- of the skill being set-up for.

Do not include secondaries or generals in set-up base chance and do not
include the difficulty of the skill.  Only include the RAW SUCCESS CHANCE:
RANK*10 + LVF.  This is because the more difficult actions are where set-up
is really needed and IMO makes the most difference in real-life.

The set-up skill allows you to double the set-up bonus per count for the
first RANK counts of set-up.

--- --- ---
          ON SUPPORT SKILLS

You may no longer roll against support skills.  They give their
3% per rank or 1 SPD point per rank and that is it.  This change alleviates
two problems:

(1) People have been getting high bonuses because they are criticalling
their support skill rolls.  This is often because of level factor and other
bonuses that already give to the primary skill, so they are redundant
bonuses.

(2) This change reduces the number of rolls people have to make in play.
Your quickstrike just adds Rank in SPD points to your action.  Period!  Your
florentine gives you 3% per rank- period.  No need to do another roll- no
need to recalculate for levels of success, etc.
This is a blessing for people with low ranks because it means you don't fail
your roll either- you always get 6% for your rank 2 support skill!:-)

Support skills can go above the negative modifier for a skill. (I.e. a RANK
15 Florentine character gets +45% and the minus is only minus 40%.  This
person is 5% better florentining than not florentining.)

NOTE: Some support skills must be rolled against as a primary to ""activate""
their effect.  This is a binary on/off roll- there is no critical possible
but the roll must be successful to use the support skill.  These activation
rolls typically take 4 counts.

You may use as many support skills as applicable skills you are using.  If
you have unused support skills they may be used as secondaries.

Whenever it is not stated what the contribution of a secondary, support or
general skill  is- but you know it makes a contribution- you can assume it
contributes:
3% per RANK to-hit
(RANK - 2)/2 to SPD
(RANK - 2)/2 to DAM

Note that some support skills do not contribute to-hit or def: Quickstrike,
Quickdraw

Some do not contribute to SPD: Called Shot, Set-Up, Evasion,  Armor Wearing,
Great Blow

Some do not contribute to  DAM: Called Shot, Quick Strike, Quick Draw,
Feint, Parry, Set-up. Evasion, Armor Wearing, Instant Attack, Great Blow

ON INSTANT ATTACK
Instant attacks are attacks in which the initiative roll is automatically
adjusted to 0.  It is declared at a reaction, a normal attack is launched
and then the next attack begins the sequence with an INIT roll of 0 .

The penalties are -40 for the first instant attack, -50 for the next one,
and -60 for all following instant attacks.  The first instant attack is
defined as the first attack to happen after the adjusted initiative.

As with pre-sets the actions must be declared at the reaction.  Each action
must be specifically declared.  One can declare up to (RANK + DRIVE/3)
actions.  Recurring loops are possible.  For instance: I block high and then
I hit him again and again and again and don't stop till he is dead......

ON KI FOCUS

Ki Focus is a separate skill that has no speed effects.  It takes 10 counts
to do, and is good for one action.  It allows the user to pour KI(MEN) into
damage and to-hit chance.  The to-hit bonus for this will also be limited to
the Raw SC=> (RANK*10+LVF) or the max damage of the attack.  Adds RANK/4
to-hit or RANK/8 in damage per MEN used.

It is also a prerequisite for several ""monkish"" skills: Body Control, Iron
Skin, Reduce Exhaustion.

ON TRANCES (MAGE, BATTLE, KI, etc.)

These also cannot be criticalled- They will make perceptions and all
applicable skills easier (15% + 3% per rank).  When a trance is induced a
specific perception is activated.  You must roll to enter a trance.  It
takes 30 counts, and no crit effects can be used for to-hit modification,
although you could use the success levels for other things...

The pluses here are also limited to the raw success chance of the primary
skill being modified.

ON KATA

A Kata is a support skill(I.e. above and beyond the secondaries and
generals) to all skills in its umbrella.  It adds 3% per RANK to-hit, and
RANK in INIT to all of its skills.  All the actions in the Kata are done as
Instant Attacks.

They are organized into ""sequences"" of 2-5 actions with reactions in
between.  One can enter or leave a sequence at the reactions in-between and
those reactions re-set the Instant Attacks. Breaking the Kata at a
non-reaction, or in the middle of a sequence,  carries a +8 penalty to the
character's next INIT (double the penalty for missing a normal action).

The Kata would have to be activated with a successful roll, though no crit
would be possible as in all support skills.  It takes 4 counts to activate a
Kata. Every sequence written into a Kata beyond the first adds -10% to the
activation roll of the Kata.

Summary:
Kata are composed of a number of sequences.
Each sequence has 2-5 actions.
Each sequence is treated as a series of instant attacks.
The first action of a sequence is a normal attack.
Breakout can occur between sequences, or with a penalty.
Katas are 'simple activation' skills, with no crit potential.
Kata skills add 3% per rank to all actions in the Kata.

BEGIN EXAMPLE:

Bob the Paladin decides he wants to use his ""squish 'em, gish 'em, turn 'em""
Kata.

COUNT 0
(1)He rolls a reaction.  He acts in 2 counts.

COUNT 2
(2)When his action comes he says 'I activate ""squish 'em, gish 'em, turn
'em"" '.  He rolls his Kata skill as a Primary and succeeds.  He declares
what sequence he will use(this Kata only has one) and that he will start
right into the Kata. (SEE OPTION 2 BELOW)
It takes him 4 counts to do this.

COUNT 6
(3)He takes the first action of the Kata without rolling initiative.  He
automatically gets a zero and starts the action on count six.  He gets  all
his SPD as ACT points and takes a -40(modified by RANK*3 in the KATA).  It
takes him 2 counts after ACT mods to squish.

COUNT 8
(4) He starts right into gishing.  It takes him 2 counts after ACT mods and
he takes a -50(modified by RANK*3 in the KATA).

COUNT 10
(5)He starts his 10-count ""Prot Vs. Nasties"".  It takes him five counts
after ACT mods and he is at a -60 (modified by RANK*3 in the KATA).

COUNT 15
(6)He rolls his Turn successfully and the turn goes off and he rolls a
reaction roll- now 3 seconds after deciding to go into the Kata in the first
place.

OPTION 2: After successfully rolling KATA, you can roll a reaction and then
act so that the first action of the Kata isn't at -40, it is as a normal
action, and the second action is the first instant attack.

ON FEINTS

A feint is a false attack designed to create an opening in an opponent's
defense. It is a contest between the feinter's skill at feint and the
opponent's perception. The formula for the success of a feint is:

FSC = (Feinter's RANK in weapon being used)*10 + LVF + MODS + (Feinter's
RANK in Feint)*3

The success of the feint is based on the Success Level of the Opponent's
Perception roll.  How well the feinter succeeded is then subtracted from
their opponents perception.

The feint takes weapon speed(WSD) of the weapon used divided by two in
counts to execute.

A successful feint adds 40% to-hit, halves opponent's defense, and increases
ACT by 10.

An unsuccessful feint subtracts 40% to-hit, and minus 8 from the feinter's
next INIT.

If the attacker had failed his feint AND the defender had still badly failed
his per roll, then the blade would still be drawn away but the attacker
would only be at -20% to-hit and minus 4 to the next INIT.

The feinter then rolls reaction as per pre-set and attacks.

Here is an example of Bob the Paladin feinting:

BEGIN EXAMPLE
(BOB finishes up an action and announces he is going to feint with his
sword.)

COUNT 0
BOB: I am going to feint.
(He rolls initiative, modified by his skill in feint with sword as a
secondary OR sword with feint [feint adds {RANK-2}/2 to SPD when used as a
support skill])
BOB: I will react in 2 counts!

COUNT 2
GM: There is a possible opening to the shoulder. (Generated by random
location chart)
Bob: I feint an attack to the shoulder to draw his weapon away from his
head. (Bob determines his sword feint-at half his normal weapon speed, then
modified by his ACT points- will take 2 counts)

COUNT 4
(Bob rolls his feint.  GM rolls defenders perception modified by the
attacker's feint success.  In this case, the defender fails.)
GM: An opening appears at the defender's head.
(Bob determines how long his real attack takes including the feint mods
etc-say 3 counts-)
Bob: I attack and will hit in 3 counts!

COUNT 7
Bob: I roll to hit. (Bob rolls to-hit at called shot minuses for head but at
plus 40 for the successful feint and only taking half the defender's
defense.)   I hit!!!  Yea!!!!
(Bob rolls reaction to do some new action that he announces now.  If he had
failed the feint he would have to add 8 points to his INIT on this roll....)

END EXAMPLE

--- --- ---
         ON MOVEMENT MODS

It is exceedingly difficult to target an opponent that is moving.
Therefore these are the mods:

If you are moving at all: -40% to-hit
(Possible support skill: Shoot-While-Move.  Adds 3% per rank to your shot.)

If your target is moving at all: -40% to-hit
(Possible support skill: Targeting Perception.  If you make an ACTIVE
targeting perception- I.e. follow the target, lead the target- that is
successful you cut all the target based movement mods in half- including the
velocity differential.)

For every foot per count your velocities are different: -10% to-hit.
(NOTE: If the velocity differential is at a significant angle- less than 45
degrees- then you may reduce the minuses in direct relation to the angle*2
as a percentage.  I.e. If it is at 45 degrees then you can  take 90% of the
velocity differential minuses[9% per ft/ct instead of ten]. If it is heading
straight towards or straight away it is 0% and you take no velocity
differential but still take the opponent moving mod.)

An opponent is defined as moving if they:
(a) have a velocity greater than 1 ft/count, or
(b) are engaged in a maneuver skill of some sort (dodge, acrobatics,
gymnastics, running, swimming, falling, actively riding).  Climbing or
defense is usually not counted unless the climber/defender can fulfill
condition (a).

Another mod is ""Unstable Platform"": -40%.  Includes: moving cars,
helicopters, crumbling/unsteady standing/kneeling/lying surface

