"Re: Replies to people from Alex #1, 01/13/98","My random thoughts on several topics

GUNS
   With a high modifier for stationary targets BT matches my (limited)
experience much better.  This on top of your high mods for movement just magnify
the difference motion makes all the more.  (Not necessarily a problem).  Sucks
to be a sniper though--I guess that's why they always hide so far away.
   I think the movement mods are actually pretty reasonable.  (I am assuming
that target movement speed is _relative_ to the shooter.)  One MPH equals
roughly .3 ft/count.  Roughly a -10% for every 3 MPH, so a car going 60 MPH
would be -200%, -40% for any motion = -240%.  A successful MCP perception would
cut it to -120%.  With set-up, design level mods for angle of approach and other
positive modifiers, these numbers seem pretty reasonable.  Presumably a critical
MCF perception would further decrease the movement mods?

KATA
   Why roll to activate a kata?  As long as you don't let them be abused (can
Stephen have a called-shot head, called-shot head, called-shot head kata? ;-)
they seem to be fairly limited in their application.  How many players have ever
bothered with them?  I'd just make them a normal support skill.  Also, I
understood the mechanism for switching between katas to be different.  The way I
designed my system (which I thought came out of a discussion Alex and I had) is
that if you have two kata, A-B-C-D and X-Y-B-Z, you could switch at B if you
declared it before commiting action B (sort of like declaring a pre-set).  Not
quite as powerful and I think fairly realistic.

FEINTS
   I agree with Mark that feint mods are too harsh in each direction.  At best a
feint should cancel an opponents defense, parry, etc., not give you +40 to hit. 
You are canceling his ability to avoid your blow, not convincing him to spit
himself on the end of your sword.  I like the idea of a changing level of effect
based on success (but you knew I would).

ON ACT AND CRIT LEVELS
   I also do not like the idea of rolling before an action, primarily for
suspense reasons.  There are also lots more playability reasons.  When do you
declare a preset?  What if you are wounded before your action finishes?
   Thinking out loud here...You can currently take a minus to hit to increase
speed at -10% = 1 SPD (or ACT, or whatever they are today ;-)  Trading critical
effect for ACT is essentially the same thing.  In fact, for all but the first
two SLs, 40%/4 = 10% crit effect, so 1 crit level should give you 4 SPD.   What
if you ""wagered"" crit levels the same way you do with called shot mods?  If you
