--- --- ---
          ON TYPES OF SKILLS

In Bardic Tales the interface between the player and the actions their
character takes is the ""skills"" of the character.  A skill is a piece of
knowledge or training or automatic behavior that a character has that allows
them to take an action.  Skills include things like knowing how to build a
car, flying a helicopter, swinging a sword in combat, identifying someone's
emotional state, noticing a hidden ambusher, or cooking a great ham.

Skills can be used in a variety of ways and come in several types.  The
types of skills are: primary, secondary, tertiary, general, and support.
There is an optional type called related skills discussed here as well.

All skills in Bardic Tales fit into one or more of these categories. How to
apply the skill depends on what category it is in. Bear in mind that these
types of skills only apply on a per application basis. Most skills can be
used in at least three ways: A skill that is used as the Primary skill for a
given roll may be used as a Secondary, Tertiary, or even General Skill for a
later roll, depending on the task at hand.

Some of these skills merely act as modifiers while others need to be rolled.
This skill breakdown is an attempt to codify and methodize something that in
real life is the result of at least hundreds of factors and conditions.
This is a vast simplification.  Please bear that in mind.

***
Primary Skills

Primary skills are the primary use of the skill. If you were shooting
someone with a Walther PPK, for example, your pistol skill would be the
primary skill.   If you do not have a skill in the correct area your RANK is
considered to be 0 (unless you have a related skill.  See the Option Rule
re: Related Skills)

Primary skills are calculated by adding RANK*10 to Level Factor(LVF).  This
gives the Base Success Chance(BSC). The BSC can be modified by situation and
environmental factors.  There can only be one primary skill for each action.

Primary skills add ([RANK] - 2) to both SPeeD(SPD) and EFFect(DAM).

Primary Skill Effect Summary:
BC=10%/RANK,  SPD=RANK -2,  DAM=RANK-2

***
Secondary Skills

Secondary skills are skills that are closely related to the primary, that
use similar tools, are appropriate lore skills, or operate in the same
general area.  They add to the person's chance, speed and effectiveness with
a particular skill.

Here is a list of some primaries and their possible secondaries:
  Pistol: rifle and Targeting Perception
  Fist: Foot and Elbow-Strike
  Power Blast: Psi Shield and SCF Set-up
  Sword: Knife and Mace
  Driving Car: Pilot Helicopter and Car Lore

Secondary skills are calculated as [RANK]*3 added to the primary skill they
are supporting.  You can only pick two secondary skills for each primary
skill roll.

Secondary skills add ([RANK] - 2)/2 to both the SPD and DAM of the primary
skill. The value for these is never negative.

Secondary Skill Effect Summary:
BC = 3%/RANK,  SPD = (RANK - 2)/2,  DAM = (RANK - 2)/2

***
Tertiary Skills

Tertiary skills are vaguely related skills that assist the character in
performing the primary skill.  Any skill that can be a secondary can also be
a tertiary, and even a vague connection to the primary skill is usually
sufficient to convince the GM to let you use a skill as a tertiary!:-)

Tertiary skills are calculated as [RANK]*1% added to the primary. You can
only pick two tertiary skills for each primary skill roll.

Tertiary skills do not add SPD and DAM bonuses.

Tertiary Skill Effect Summary:
BC = 1%/RANK

***
Support Skills

Support skills are skills which are particularly designed to support or
enhance another skill. They often model a variation or particular action
that is a use of a primary skill. Some examples are: Florentine, Parry,
Called Shot, Quickstrike, Great Blow, Lunge, etc.

Support Skills are typically linked to a family of skills not just one
particular skill. You wouldn't have ""Quickstrike: Long Sword"" you would have
""Quickstrike: Bladed Weapons"". Support skills are locked- not any skill can
be a support skill.  The prefix for a support skill is ""S:"".

There is no limit to the number of support skills one can use with a primary
so long as one is performing the action they apply to. If you have unused
support skills they may be used as secondaries(see description above).

NOTE: Some support skills must be rolled against as a primary to ""activate""
their effect.  There are two kinds of this roll- the activation roll and the
use roll.

The Activation roll:
This is a binary on/off roll- the roll must be successful to use the support
skill but there are no critical effects possible to-hit. Success levels can
be used, though, to generate any non to-hit related bonuses.  These
activation rolls typically take 4 counts.  Kata and Florentine are examples
of support skills that one must activate.

The Use roll:
In this case the support skill is rolled as a primary, with the main skill
as a secondary.  Typically this is as a contest of skills.  In that case the
roll is treated as a primary.  Feint is an example of a use roll skill.  If
a support skill requires a use roll it will be detailed in the skill
description- support skills default to the mode described elsewhere in this
section.

Support skills do not add SPD or DAM bonuses unless they are specifically
designed to do so. If not specified elsewhere they add 3% per [RANK].
However, each support skill can have its own special functions so refer to
<Appendix G: Combat Options and Support Skills> in the User's Guide.

  Note that some support skills do not contribute to-hit or def:
Quickstrike,   Quickdraw

  Some do not contribute to SPD: Called Shot, Set-Up, Evasion, Armor
Wearing, Great Blow

  Some do not contribute to DAM: Called Shot, Quick Strike, Quick Draw,
  Feint, Parry, Set-up. Evasion, Armor Wearing, Instant Attack, Great Blow

Support skills can go above the negative modifier for a skill. (i.e. a RANK
15 Florentine character gets +45% and the minus is only minus 40%.  This
person is 5% better florentining than not florentining.)

Support Skill Effect Summary:
BC = 3%/RANK (sometimes) - VARIES WITH SKILL DESCRIPTION. SEE RULES OR GM.

***
General Skills

General skills are umbrella skills that include a whole group of skills in
their domain. Martial styles and Schools of Wizardry are examples of general
skills. Only skills that are primaries should be put in a general skill. A
framework for a generic General skill could include:

  Appropriate Lore skill
  Appropriate Perception skill
  + 5 or so Primary skills that make the pattern.

Note that the content of a general skill is fairly flexible.  It is not
locked in stone.  Some general skills require an activation roll- that is
the character must use an action - or ACT points- to roll the General skill
as a primary to begin applying the mods to their skills.
General skills are locked- not any skill can be a general skill.  The prefix
for a general skill is either G: or W: .

General skills add 3% to-hit per rank, and (RANK - 2)/2 SPD/DAM. Most things
have at least one applicable General skill.   You can only have one general
skill per primary skill roll.

General Skill Examples

Parentheses indicate support skills that should be taken to complete the
General.

  G:Shotokan Karate->
     Shotokan Lore, Combat Perception,
     Punch (great blow; lunge; called shot; instant attack),
     Kick (great blow; lunge; called shot),
     Block (great blow; lunge), Combat Movement, Kata, Dojo Cul. Lore

  G:Aikido->
     Aikido Lore, Combat Perception, Throw (quick-strike),
     Hold (quick-strike; nerve-technique), Defense, Release,
     Acrobatics, Dojo Culture Lore

  G:Tae-Kwon-Do->
     Tae-Kwon-Do Lore, Combat Perception,
     Kick (quick-strike; great-blow; spinning), Jumping, Block,
     Punch, Kata

  G:Fencing->
     Fencing lore, Combat Perception,
     Sword (quick-strike, called shot, lunge, feint),
     Parry (disarm, quick-strike), Combat Movement, Accelerate

  W:Wizardry Alteration->
     Alteration Lore, SCF Perception,
     M: <any Alteration Ritual or Spell>, S: Change Form,
     S: Alter Shape, R:<Alteration runes>,
     L: <Alteration casting language>, Magical School History

General Skill Effect Summary:
BC = 3%/RANK,  SPD = (RANK - 2)/2,  DAM =  (RANK - 2)/2

***
Related Skills (Optional Rule)

A BT Related Skill is a non-additive replacement skill for a primary skill.
It must be close enough to the primary skill that a percentage of it can be
applied to the success chance INSTEAD of the that primary skill. Example:

I have a RANK 5 in drive truck. I jump in the car. I have RANK 1 in Drive
car. They are RELATED at 4/5. This means when I calculate out my chance to
drive car, I can use 4/5 of my truck RANK to drive the car INSTEAD OF the
RANK 1 in Drive Car. It is useful because if you can drive a truck at rank 5
you can CERTAINLY drive a car at least 60-80% of your chance. However they
are not really additive- you shouldn't get 3/4 or 4/5 of your truck RANK to
add to your CAR rank because the principles are very similar.
However you can use your RANK one in DRIVE CAR as a secondary (3% per rank,
etc)

***
SKILL CHANCES

All this is designed to generate the percentage chance of the character
fulfilling on a particular task.  This final chance is called the Final
Success Chance(FSC).  The formula summarizing the effects of the various
skill types on the FSC is:

FSC = Primary Skill Rank *10
      + [Secondary Skill Rank] *3 + [Secondary Skill Rank] *3
      + [Tertiary Skill Rank] + [Tertiary Skill Rank]
      + [General Skill Rank] *3
      + [Any Support Skills' Ranks] *3
      + [Appropriate Level Factor]
      + MODS + DIFF_MOD

Not every slot will be filled for every action- a character may not have
applicable skills for any of the slots. Note that square brackets [ ] around
a value means that value is truncated(i.e. 4.6 becomes 4). More information
on SITUATIONAL MODS can be found in the success chance section of Chapter 2:
System Rules and in the Situational Modifiers table in Chapter 3: Combat

RAW SUCCESS CHANCE(RSC) = Primary*10 + LVF

BASE SUCCESS CHANCE(BSC) = Primary*10 + LVF + DIFF_MOD

FINAL SUCCESS CHANCE(FSC) = Primary*10 +2Secondaries*3 + 2Tertiaries*1 +
1General*3 + Supportskills*3 + LVF + DIFF_MOD + MODS

DIFF_MOD = Difficulty modifier for the action or tool being used.
MODS= Situational, or environmental modifiers to the action
NOTE: No skill can appear in the Final Success chance more than once.

--- --- ---
          ON CRITICALS/SUCCESS LEVELS

It is axiomatic to most RPGs and realism simulations that there is a chance
for particularly good successes.  Out of this, the concept of ""criticals"" or
""success levels"" comes.
In BT the distinctions are now made along these breakpoints:

SN = Success number = number you need to roll to succeed in the skill- this
is your FSC.

CSN = Critical Success Number = 1/4 of your SN.

CFN = Critical Failure Number = SN + 50

SL = Success Level

NOTE: In these discussions we will speak about damage and effect
interchangeably.  Mostly this is an artifact of the skill system growing out
of a gaming system that focused on modeling weapon effects.  However the
pluses to Damage(DAM), and the multipliers for effect are both modeling the
same area.  For purposes of weapons effect is damage and for purposes of
non-weapon skills DAM is the same as effect.

     Effect of Success Levels on Effect
At or under the success number:  SL 1  skill applied,half-effect
At or under half the SN:         SL 2        full-effect
At or under quarter the SN(CSN): SL 3        1.5* effect
At or under CSN-10:              SL 4        2* effect
At or under CSN-20:              SL 5        2.5* effect
At or under CSN-30:              SL 6        3* effect etc.

     Success Levels also measure levels of failure:
Over the success number:    SL +0  missed to-hit, action not successful
Over SN by 50(CFN):         SL -1  -20% to save or recovery roll
Over CFN+10:                SL -2  -40% to save or recovery roll
Over CFN+20:                SL -3  -60% to save or recovery roll
Over CFN+30:                SL -4  -80% to save or recovery roll

To get the damage modifier of a hit, divide the SL by 2.  That is the effect
multiplier.  This assumes you are using your SLs for effect.  Negative SLs
subtract 20% per negative SL from the appropriate save or recovery roll.

You could also use them for reducing END cost(see Endurance section for
success level effect on Endurance), or increasing effect duration(mechanism
to be determined), or effect control(mechanism to be determined), or some
other things I am sure you will all think of....

NOTE: It is advisable to always put at least one level of success into
effect/damage or you will have no effect!:-)(Although I can see in a
proactive fight you might put all your success levels into endurance cost or
showmanship or something...)

     Effect of Success Levels on Endurance
1 x2/3
2 x1/2
3 x2/5
4 x1/3
5 x2/7
6 x1/4
...
     Effect of Success Levels on INIT points
SL INIT
1  +2
2  +4
3  +6
4  +8
5  +10
6  +12

NOTE:  INIT points from SL(SL*1.5, round down) go towards the reaction
IMMEDIATELY after the action (i.e. the character is so much smoother with
the action they can transition into the next action better.
...
The SL is the amount {(CSN - number rolled)/10 + 3 [rounded down]} for all
successes below SL 2.

Example:

SN=100 so CSN=25.

I roll a 66.  This is a SL 1. One level of success.
*
I roll a 43.  That is a SL 2.  It is two levels of success to apply
to whatever I want.  One could apply both levels to effect(full damage), OR
one level to effect(1/2 damage) and one level to reducing endurance(2/3
endurance cost).
*
I roll a 22.  That is a SL 3.  It is three levels of success to play
with.
I could put one to Endurance(2/3 cost) and two to effect(full damage)
or all three to effect(1.5*damage)
or one to INIT points(2 points), one to Endurance(2/3 cost), and one to
Effect(.5*damage).
*
I roll a 13.  That is a SL 4.  It is four levels of success to play with.
I could put three to effect(1.5*damage) and one to endurance(2/3 cost),
or one to effect(1.5*damage) and three to endurance(2/5 cost), etc.

End Example.

