          ON TIME

Managing flow of actions, sequencing of occurrences, and time-flow in Bardic
Tales is modeled by breaking time up into discrete units called counts.
Each count is the equivalent of a fifth of a second.

There is a system called ""initiative"" that manages when a character acts and
reacts in counts.  This is based on a series of variables including the
primary stats AGL, DSC, and INT; the secondary stats of Physical Speed(PSPD)
or Mental Speed(MSPD); the Total Level Factor of the character(TLF); the
Physical Level Factor(PLF) or Mental Level Factor(MLF), and the Level Factor
of the skill being used in the action.  This ""initiative"" also includes the
person's RANK in the skill about to be used, and in the similar skills
supporting it, the character's physical well-being, mental state, and other
situational modifiers.  These variables are all bundled together under a
single number called SPD.

To simulate the variability of our interface with the world, the
""initiative"" is generated by rolling two 6-sided dice and adding them
together and then modifying them by SPD/2(rounded up).  The resultant number
is the number of counts a character must wait until they can start an
action.  This is their ""reaction time"" in counts.

During the course of a combat or specific interaction, the GM will walk
through time count by count. In each count there is an action phase and then
a reaction phase.   When a person ""rolls initiative"" and generates a number,
that number is the number of counts the person takes to ""react"" to their
environment and start an action.  If the number is negative(due to
modifiers) then it is declared as zero counts and the person can declare
what action they are starting in the reaction phase of that count, and it
will start in the action phase of the next count.

All negative initiative(plus SPD/2[rounded down]) gets turned into ACTION
POINTS(ACT), which can be used to speed up the time it actually takes to do
the action.

Each action has a speed assigned to it.  This is called WeaponSpeed(WSD-
this is another layover from the time when all skills were modeling
combat!).  This speed is also a measure of the ""counts"" it takes to perform
the action.   So once the person is finished reacting(in the reaction phase
of the count their reaction completes) they would confirm which action they
were starting in the action phase of the next count.  That would be the
first count of the action.  When they reach the action phase of the count
which is (modified WSD) counts later they would roll their skill roll and
the action would take place.

Some skill options that change this slightly are pre-sets and instant
attacks.  The only difference is that when using a pre-set you roll 2d6/2
instead of 2d6 for the reaction variation.  In an instant attack you proceed
as if you had ROLLED a 0[normally impossible] on your 2d6/2 pre-set roll.

SPEED mechanics are explained in more detail below.

--- --- ---
          ON SPEED

Speed Points(SPD) => the number generated by the character's PSPD/MSPD stat,
plus the LVF/10, plus the RANK modifiers: primary(RANK-2),
secondaries([RANK-2]/2), and general([RANK-2]/2), plus any SPECIAL
POINTS(Support skills like Quickstrike, Environmental variables, Physical
and Mental state of the character)

Initiative points(INIT) => the number subtracted from the characters
initiative roll.  It is equal to half the speed points, rounded up. Is added
to directly by some SUPPORT SKILLS like Kata.

Action Points(ACT) => the points used to speed up actions, perform passive
actions or add to-hit.  It is equal to half the speed points, rounded down.
Is added to directly by some SUPPORT SKILLS like Quickdraw

Negative initiative turns into ACT on a 1 per 1 basis.

Quickstrike generates 1 SPD per RANK.    Kata generates 1 INIT per RANK.  A
specific Quickdraw skill generates 1 ACT per RANK.

To buy 1 ACT => 10% to-hit or 3 points of damage(only for muscle-powered,
non-stored-energy weapons) or 1 negative initiative

One ACT will buy you:  2%-to-hit or 1/3 DAM or 1 count off of a passive
action.

Examples of passive actions: perception[8 counts], support skill
initiation[usually 8 counts], general skill activation[usually 8 counts,
Kata [not a general skill but a support skill that required activation- is 4
counts], etc.  So 8 ACTION points will buy you a full passive perception or
general skill activation.

--- --- ---
          ON SETUP

Set-up in real counts will give you 5% per count and is limited to:

(1) 10 + KIF/2 counts of set-up AND

(2) a maximum value equal to  (RANK*10+LVF)- or the default value(saves,
MAP, etc.)- of the skill being set-up for.

Do not include secondaries or generals in set-up base chance and do not
include the difficulty of the skill.  Only include the RAW SUCCESS CHANCE:
RANK*10 + LVF.  This is because the more difficult actions are where set-up
is really needed and IMO makes the most difference in real-life.

The set-up skill allows you to double the set-up bonus per count for the
first RANK counts of set-up.

ON INSTANT ATTACK

Instant attacks are attacks in which the initiative roll is
automatically adjusted to 0.  It is declared at a reaction, a normal attack
is launched and then the next attack begins the sequence with an INIT roll
of 0 .

The penalties are -40 for the first instant attack, -50 for the next one,
and -60 for all following instant attacks.  The first instant attack is
defined as the first attack to happen after the adjusted initiative.

As with pre-sets the actions must be declared at the reaction.  Each action
must be specifically declared.  One can declare up to (RANK + DRIVE/3)
actions.  Recurring loops are possible.  For instance: I block high and then
I hit him again and again and again and don't stop till he is dead......

ON KI FOCUS

Ki Focus is a primary skill that allows the user to pour KI(MEN) into damage
and to-hit chance.  It takes 10 counts to do, and is good for one action.
The to-hit bonus for this is limited to the Raw Success Chance(RSC-
RANK*10+LVF), and the DAM bonus is limited to the max normal damage of the
attack.  Adds RANK/4 to-hit or RANK/8 in damage per MEN used.

It is a prerequisite for several ""monkish"" skills: Body Control, Iron Skin,
Reduce Exhaustion.

ON TRANCE (Mage Trance, Battle Trance, Ki Trance etc.)

Trances are primary skills that allow the character to enter an altered
state focused in a particular area.  On entering the trance the appropriate
perception is activated and all other perceptions are cut in half.  The
trance will make that perception and all applicable skills easier (15% + 3%
per rank).  You must roll to enter a trance, but no success levels can be
used to modify the to-hit mods.  It takes 30 counts to activate.

The to-hit bonuses are limited to the raw success chance of the primary
skill being modified

ON KATA

A Kata (a Japanese word for a martial art form) is a series of specific
skills strung together to be performed sequentially as a training tool and
to develop speed, flow, and prowess in a particular, specific set of uses of
the skills in the kata.

Kata typically refers to martial skills, but it doesn't need to be. Any
group of skills could be put together into a kata. The key is that the
skills need to have specific applications. For instance, strikes need to
specify high, low, or mid-range strikes, and they need to specify support
skills used- if any.

A Kata is a support skill to all the skills in its umbrella.  It adds 3% per
RANK to-hit, and RANK in INIT to all of its skills.  All the actions in the
Kata are done as Instant Attacks.

They are organized into ""sequences"" of 2-5 actions with reactions in
between.  One can enter or leave a sequence at the reactions in-between and
those reactions re-set the Instant Attacks. Breaking the Kata at a
non-reaction, or in the middle of a sequence,  carries a +8 penalty to the
character's next INIT (double the penalty for missing a normal action).

The Kata would have to be activated with a successful roll, though no crit
would be possible as in all support skills.  It takes 4 counts to activate a
Kata. Every sequence written into a Kata beyond the first adds -10% to the
activation roll of the Kata.

Summary:
Kata are composed of a number of sequences.
Each sequence has 2-5 actions.
Each sequence is treated as a series of instant attacks.
The first action of a sequence is a normal attack.
Breakout can occur between sequences, or with a penalty.
Katas are 'simple activation' skills, with no crit potential.
Kata skills add 3% per rank to all actions in the kata.

BEGIN EXAMPLE:

Bob the Paladin decides he wants to use his ""squish 'em, gish 'em, turn 'em""
Kata.

COUNT 0

(1)He rolls a reaction.  He reacts in 2 counts.

COUNT 2

(2)When his reaction comes he says 'I activate ""squish 'em, gish 'em, turn
'em"" '.    He declares what sequence he will use(this Kata only has one) and
that he will start right into the Kata. (SEE OPTION 2 BELOW)
It takes him 4 counts to do this.

COUNT 6

(3)He rolls his Kata skill as a Primary and succeeds.  He automatically gets
a zero initiative roll because he is instant attacking and starts the action
on count seven.  He gets  all his SPD as ACT points.  It takes him 2 counts
after ACT mods to squish.

COUNT 8

(4) He squishes successfully even with the -40(modified by RANK*3 in the
KATA).  He starts right into gishing.  It takes him 2 counts after ACT mods.

COUNT 10

(5)He gishes successfully even with a -50(modified by RANK*3 in the KATA).
He starts his 10-count ""Prot vs. Nasties"".  It takes him five counts after
ACT mods.

COUNT 15

(6)He rolls his Turn successfully despite the -60 (modified by RANK*3 in the
KATA). He rolls a reaction roll- now 3 seconds after deciding to go into the
Kata in the first place.

OPTION 2: After successfully rolling KATA(in ct 6 of the example), you can
roll a reaction(instead of instant attacking) and then act so that the first
action of the Kata isn't at -40, it is as a normal action, and the second
action is the first instant attack.

ON FEINTS

A feint is a false attack designed to create an enhanced opportunity to
strike and an opening in an opponent's defense. It is a contest between the
feinter's skill at feint and the opponent's perception. Feint is a support
skill.

The feinter first strikes with the feint to draw away the opponent's
defenses.  The feint's speed is weapon speed(WSD) of the weapon used,
divided by two.   The Success Level(SL) of the feint is determined as a
contest of skills between the feinter's feint and the perception of their
opponent.  Then, the feinter rolls reaction as per pre-set and attacks with
the real attack.

The formula for the success of a feint is:

FSC = FSC of Feint as a primary skill(it can use the weapon skill as a
secondary)

The success of the feint is based on the Success Level of the Opponent's
Perception roll.  The SLs the feinter generated are then subtracted from
their opponent's perception SLs.   So:

SL of feint = SL(opponent's perception) - SL(feint roll)

A successful feint adds 40% to-hit, halves opponent's defense, and increases
ACT by 10.
An unsuccessful feint subtracts 40% to-hit, and subtracts 8 from the
feinter's next INIT.

Here is an example of Bob the Paladin feinting:

BEGIN EXAMPLE

(BOB finishes up an action and announces he is going to feint with his
sword.)

COUNT 0

BOB: I am going to feint.

(He rolls initiative, modified by his skill in feint with sword as a
secondary.)

BOB: I will react in 2 counts!

COUNT 2

GM: There is a possible opening to the shoulder. (Generated by random
location chart)

Bob: I feint an attack to the shoulder to draw his weapon away from his
head.

(Bob determines that his sword feint-at half his normal weapon speed, then
modified by his ACT points- will take 2 counts)

COUNT 4

(Bob rolls his feint.  GM rolls defenders perception.  Then he subtracts the
feinter's SLs from the opponent's perception SLs.  In this case, the
opponent fails.)

GM: An opening appears at the defender's head.

(Bob rolls his pre-set initiative.  It comes to 1 count.)

COUNT 5

(Bob determines how long his real attack takes including the feint mods
etc-say 3 counts-)

Bob: I attack and will hit in 3 counts!

COUNT 8

Bob: I roll to hit. (Bob rolls to-hit at called shot minuses for head but at
plus 40 for the successful feint and only taking half the defender's
defense.)   I hit!!!  Yea!!!!

(Bob rolls reaction to do some new action that he announces now.  If he had
failed the feint he would have lost 8 points of his INIT on this roll....)

END EXAMPLE

--- --- ---
         ON MOVEMENT MODS

It is exceedingly difficult to target an opponent that is moving.
Therefore these are the mods:

If you are moving at all: -40% to-hit
(Possible support skill: Shoot-While-Move.  Adds 3% per rank to your shot.)

If your target is moving at all: -40% to-hit
(Possible support skill: Targeting Perception.  If you make an ACTIVE
targeting perception- i.e. follow the target, lead the target- that is
successfull you cut all the target based movement mods in half- including
the velocity differential.)

For every foot per count your velocities are different: -10% to-hit.
(NOTE: If the velocity differential is at a significant angle- less than 45
degrees- then you may reduce the minuses in direct relation to the angle*2
as a percentage.  I.e. If it is at 45 degrees then you can  take 90% of the
velocity differential minuses[9% per ft/ct instead of ten]. If it is heading
straight towards or straight away it is 0% and you take no velocity
differential but still take the opponent moving mod.)

An opponent is defined as moving if they:
(a) have a velocity greater than 1 ft/count, or
(b) are engaged in a maneuver skill of some sort (dodge, acrobatics,
gymnastics, running, swimming, falling, actively riding).  Climbing or
defense is usually not counted unless the climber/defender can fulfill
condition (a).

Another mod is ""Unstable Platform"": -40%.  Includes: moving cars,
helicopters, crumbling/unsteady standing/kneeling/lying surface

