Okay, here it is-- ""If Myth ran the world""


1. 'Normal' skills:

        All the regular skills go here; weapons, languages, sorceries, etc.
        Represents learning of a specific action, technique, or lore.
        Rolled at (10*rank)+mods, including assisting skills.
        Rolls may be unopposed (take crit effects), or opposed (compare
SL's).
        Opposed skills subtract opponent's SL's from those rolled for the
skill.
        Normal skills can perform as secondaries and tertiaries.

2. General skills:

        All the 'G:' skills, 'W:' skills, trances, and kata go here.
        Applies to a small, medium, or large group of regular skills.
        Represents general competence in a small body of knowledge.
        Applies a fixed bonus (usually 3%/rank) to skills in the group.
        May have to roll against skill to 'activate' and obtain bonus.
        May have side effects (usually perceptual), bonuses, or penalties.
        Likliehood of side effects increases with size of skill group.
        A skill may only get a bonus from one 'free' (non-activated)
general skill.
        General skills may instead be used for secondary or tertiary
effects.

3. Support skills:

        All the skills that help offset particular penalties go here.
        Represents competence in a particular cross-skill activity.
        Applies a fixed (usually 3%/rank) bonus when performing that
activity.
        Specific support skills may have different effects; see Appendix G.
        Several different support skills may be used at once; all may apply
bonuses.
        The bonus from a support skill may be higher than the penalty for
that activity.
        Support skills may instead be used for secondary or tertiary
effects.


Skills may be assisted by up to two secondary skills, and up to two
tertiary skills.  In addition,
 there may be a number of bonuses due to one or more general skills (only
one 'free')  and 
one or more appropriate support skills.  No skill may assist more than once
in this fashion.
No skill may assist or support itself.


Notes--
General skills seem to be a special no-roll subset of 'mode' skills, or a
very small category
of their own, with huge similarities to the mode skills.  This necessitated
a few other changes
in the verbiage. 


I've also been thinking about the Feint and Parry skills and decided that
(maybe) Alex was right.

Option 1 for them seems to be as support skills for special maneuvers. 
This means it is more
        important what weapon you are using (10%/rank) than what maneuver
you are trying
        with it (3%/rank).  This seems to make logical sense to me, despite
my earlier
        protests.

Option 2 would be as primary skills, with the weapon skill serving as a
secondary.  This sounded
        well and good until I started working through the implications. 
First among those, of
        course, is the fact that feinting or parrying skill would be more
important (10%/rank)
        than skill in the weapon used (3%/rank).  While this might be
arguable, particularly
        without weapons at hand, it does not make logical sense to me,
again despite my
        earlier protests.

So, Alex, you were right and I was wrong.  Sorry for hassling you so much
on the subject.

