"Re: Experience Points","Ron asked how to do eeps.  Here is a quickie  discussion and example:

Formula for Target Number(TN)

TN = RANK*10 - XPM - LVF/10

XPM = the Experience Point Modifier secondary stat
LVF = the level factor of the skill being eeped in.

This formula gives you your target number (TN).

If you roll equal to or higher than your TN you receive +.1 to your RANK.
(I.e. if you had RANK 3.2 you would now have 3.3; if you had RANK 2 you
would now have RANK 2.1)

If you roll less than your TN you get no penalties and can add +.01 to your
rank.  HOWEVER- any hundredths additions DISAPPEAR the instant you
successfully make a roll.  I.e. you could fail 8 times and be at 2.18, but
then you make it and you go to 2.20 NOT 2.28.  Clear?

For every 40 points that you beat your TN by you can add another +.1 to your
rank.

Here is an example:

Bob has a 4.6 in the skill ""Hide"".  His XPM is 2, and his Agility
Factor(AGF) is 22.    He is putting four rolls in ""Hide""

His TN = 4.6*10 - 2 - 22/10 = 46 - 2 - 2.2 = 46 - 4.2 = 42 (round to nearest
integer for target number).

Roll 1: 96  -> This beats 42 by 54.  It is therefore worth +.2
The target number now goes up 2 to 43 because Bob's RANK is NOW 4.8.

Roll 2: 21 -> Bob fails.  It is worth +.01.
The TN is still 43.  Bob's RANK is now 4.81

Roll 3: 44 -> Bob just makes it.  It is worth +.1.
The TN is now 44.  Bob's RANK is now 4.90.

Roll 4: 187! -> This beats 44 by 143!  That is worth +.4!!!!
The TN is now 48.  Bob's RANK is now 5.3 (His AGF went up 1 point as well
but it is too small a change to effect the TN)

So in four rolls Bob went from 4.6 to 5.3.  An unlikely example but you get
the idea!:-)




