A. Improved Perception Explanation

NOTE:  Thanks to Jim and Chris for pointing out the flaws in the doc.

The secondary stat PER, MPR, and MAP all current have skill*3 in some format
attached to the secondary stat formulas.  They are disappearing.
So if I say what is your PER- I want the raw secondary stat!(Which is to say
the current formula minus the SKL portion at the end.)
So these are the formulas:

*** (begin excerpt- in btgen.htm)

PER = AUR + DSC + SKF/2 + KIF/2 + VHF/2 + PLF*2
Perception. Basis for physical perception of all kinds.

MPR = AUR + DSC + INF/2 + CTF/2 + TCF/2 + MLF*2
Mental Perception. Basis for mental perception of all kinds.

MAP = (AUR + DSC)/4 + SCF/2 + CTF/2 + DVF/2 + MLF*2
Magic Aptitude. Basis for sorceries, magical perceptions. Acts as intuition
in non-magical games.

***(end excerpt)

This then makes the write up in the system rules ACCURATE and more
comprehensible.  Here is the write up: (Chris- take note: some changes
included)

***(begin excerpt- in btstats.htm)

PERCEPTION

The basic perception stats are the secondary stats PER, MPR, and MAP.

PER(Perception) applies to physical perceptions, such as combat perception,
targeting perception, small-scale perception, movement perception or any
other perception skill that involved the five physical senses. Awareness is
the skill applied to general physical perceptions.

MPER (Mental Perception) applies to mental perceptions, such as distinguish
pattern, find reference, scan text, scan view or any other perception skill
that involves internal space. Read Pattern is the skill applied to general
mental perceptions.

MAP (Magical Aptitude) is used as a base for magical perceptions.  Sorcery
Perception(SCF PERCEPTION) is the base for this.

I will discuss perception using the physical perceptions as an example.
However MPR and MAP (when used as a perception) operate the same way.

AWARENESS(also applies to Read Pattern and SCF Perception)
Awareness is used when you are generally aware but looking for nothing in
particular. An awareness roll takes 8 counts.  If you are aware and you roll
a general perception roll (PER) you get your secondary stat plus three times
your RANK in Awareness plus two tertiaries and a general as a tertiary, or
your Awareness skill as a full Primary, whichever is higher.   That is:

SKILL_PER:
RANK[in Awareness]*10 + KIF + RANK[ in 2 secondaries]*3 + RANK[in 2
tertiaries] + RANK[ in general]*3

OR STAT_PER:
PER + RANK[in Awareness]*3 + RANK[in 2 tertiaries] + RANK[in general]*1

The tertiaries on the stat-based-formula are probably going to be the same
skills that act as secondaries for the skill-based-formula.  Also, most
people will not have a general for perception but it is included for
completeness.

SPECIFIC PERCEPTIONS
Specific perceptions (combat, targeting, sorcery, internal, small-scale,
etc.) are narrower in focus.   They act exactly as awareness does but only
for that area of perception and the appropriate skill replaces ""Awareness"",
and the appropriate level factor replaces KIF.  Magical perception (SCF) and
Divine Perception (DVF) utilize MAP as their default perception. INF
perception (INF), Craft Perception (SKF), Artistic Perception (CTF), and
Technology Perception(TCF) utilize MPR as their default.

When you activate a specific perception, your STAT_PER for those events
doubles.  Activating a perception, as this is called, drops all other
perceptions to unaware(-1 SL). To activate a specific perception you must
spend 8 counts (or less if you use ACTION points), after which your STAT_PER
is doubled for that type of perception for (DRIVE + RANK {in that specific
perception}) counts- after which you must reactivate it. The act of making a
perception roll in that specific perception is enough to activate it if you
declare it so.

Passive perception rolls are the fastest and least focussed perceptions. You
may make passive perception rolls at 0 time at any reaction. They can also
happen at a GMs discretion if the situation violently changes during a PCs
action and the PC would likely notice the change. A passive perception roll
is done at -1 Success Level.

*Unconscious(heavy sleep, unconscious, dead): -4 Success Levels on Aware
*Fully Unaware(light sleep, totally surprised): -2 Success Levels on Aware
*Unaware perceptions are: -1 Success Level on Aware perception
*Aware perception (being intentionally aware) is: STAT_PER or SKILL_PER
*Activated specific perception is: STAT_PER*2 or SKILL_PER

REMINDER: When a specific perception is activated all others become unaware.

NOTE:  SKILL_PER does NOT double because of activated perceptions- only
stat_per.  You can still choose whichever is highest.

EXAMPLE: COMBAT PERCEPTION
Most of the perceptions follow the same general rules. We will use Combat
Perception as an example- take your cues from it.

Combat Perceptions
The skill Combat Perception is more than raw perception- it is half a lore
skill- knowing how people move... knowing weapons, etc.

It takes 8 counts to make a combat perception. It lasts for [DRV + (RANK)]
counts. During that time you may make 0-count passive perception rolls as a
full primary at every reaction. Or you can make perception rolls on specific
events or conditions at 8 counts and add +1 Success Level.

If you have not taken the time to activate your perception a passive
perception roll is allowed at each reaction for SL -1.

Combat Perception Table
Success Level   RESULT
SL  -1       Beats you, you dope!
SL  0        Know that a strike is occurring,
                 know +/- 60% when it is going to strike
SL  1        +/- 30% timing of hit; OR high/low/middle
                strike location; OR hit or miss
SL   2       +/- 20% timing of hit; OR general location
                (left arm/head/chest, etc.);
SL   3        +/-10% timing of hit; OR specific location;
                OR if it is going to crit/crit miss or not.
SL    4      Two from SL 3 results

 On timing of hit, the percentages are applied to the action time. For a SL
1 (+/- 30%) versus a ten count action, you know the timing within +/-3
counts. For a 5 count action, +/-2 counts.

The player chooses how to apply the success levels. Instead of picking one
from the level that the roll indicates, the player may drop a level and pick
two, drop two levels and pick three, etc. So a SL 3 can allow a player to
know the SL 1 info on all three types of info (location, timing, and
efficacy of the blow).


Effects of Timing on Perception Rolls:

Time modifies perception rolls, on the idea that the farther an action has
progressed, the easier it is to perceive. Characters get the most efficient
time- the bonus is always evaluated from the last count of the perception
roll. If it is a passive perception it is evaluated from the count before
the passive perception.


Timing of perception Modification to perception roll

1 count before action starts -50
count before action:-4 SLs
1st half of an action: -2 SLs
3rd 1/4 of action: +0
final 1/4 of action: + 1 SLs

EFFECTS OF PERCEPTION ON DEFENSIVE ACTIONS
If you parry, block, or defend a specific part of your body/mind/whatever
you get, as a positive modifier, the modifier you would have taken if you
had made a called shot there.

A parry or block must occur in the last half of the WSD of the weapon being
parried. In other words a long sword, a ten count weapon, must be parried
within the last five counts to be effective. Uneven weapons round the parry
window time up. If the parry/block goes off before or after that window it
is not effective.

SURPRISE:
Surprise results from a critical failure on a discernment roll; or two
failures in a row on the same action; or a GM call that the person wasn't
even expecting that kind of event (i.e. a sentry not expecting trouble might
be surprised on a single failure when grabbed from behind...).

*END PERCEPTION CONVERSATION*

B. Modified Support Skill Model:

I have been struggling with how support skills interact with each other.
Thus I have looked at how they operate and I have decided to make some
changes to clarify how they operate.

Up until now people have been operating with different rules, people have
been allowed to pick between using the support skill as a secondary or using
it as a primary with the effected skill as a secondary.  Here is my
thinking:
(THIS IS A RAW THOUGHT.  INPUT WELCOME AND I AM NOT COMMITTED TO THIS):

There are primary support skills and secondary support skills.   Some
current ""support skills"" will become maneuvers.

Primary support skills are rolled as a primary skill with the skill they are
supporting acting as one of their secondaries.

Secondary support skills are additional secondaries(besides the two normally
alllowed) to the skill being supported. If the person is NOT using the
option they support they count as one of the two allowed secondaries.

Maneuvers can act as secondaries to go towards nulling out the penalties the
maneuver causes to any action done simultaneous with the maneuver.  You must
pay florentine penalties when doing the maneuver simultaneous with an
action.  (DON'T PANIC: remember maneuver-physical florentine is only -20!)

KEY:
SUPP= RANK in SUPPort skill; EFF= RANK in EFFected skill; SEC= RANK in a
secondary skill; TERT= RANK in a tertiary skill; GEN= RANK in a General
skill; LVF= appropriate level factor

PRIMARY SUPPORT SKILLS:
> > SUPP*10 + EFF*3 +SEC*3 +2 TERTs + GEN*3 + LVF + MODS
Parry/Block, Feint, Disarm, Bash, Set-Up(requires no roll though)

SECONDARY SUPPORT SKILLS:
> > EFF*10 + SUPP*3 + 2 SEC*3 + 2 TERTs +GEN*3 + LVF + MODS
Called Shot(including Nerve Strikes/Knockout, Location, etc.), Great Blow,
Quick Strike, Instant Attack, Florentine,

MANEUVERS:
> > (standard primary calculation) HOWEVER adds
> > SUPP*3 to EFF if EFF is taking minuses from
> > the action the support skill is effecting.
Lunge, Combat Maneuvers, Armor Wearing

*** END SUPPORT SKILL CONVERSATION

