Okay, it's later.  Alex, you seem to be changing perceptions from the old 
dichotomous system (physical vs. mental/magical) into more of a 
trichotomy [with apologies to the English language] of physical vs. 
intellectual vs. mystical.

I'm not against this.  In fact, it might even be a good idea.  In the 
final reckoning, it is a philosophical question and outside the scope of 
what I might reasonably complain about.  (Do not expect such petty 
considerations to stop me in the future; this is a one-time exemption.)

What I -am- against is the implementation, from a mechanics standpoint.  
MAP, as I originally learned it, was a quick-and-dirty estimate of 
general sorcerous ability, letting those with the stats have a small 
chance of minor spell-effects (incoluding detection-magics) and those 
with the skills do a lot more outside their rigidly-defined spells.  In 
the paragraphs above, you have declared it as a primary perception, 
without reformulating it at all.  To make matters worse, it still seems 
to retain its other function as well.

I think you would be better served by making a new base perception stat 
(SPER, for Spiritual PERception, perhaps), and running it much closer to 
the previous models (AUR + DSC, anyone?), and letting MAP continue solely 
in its old role.

There is also the question of whether the three-fold view is to be 
expanded to cover the rest of the primary and secondary stats as well.  I 
have no objection (again, it's a philosophical choice), but would like to 
see such a change properly thought through, rather than adopted on the 
fly.


