Hm.  Confusing.

Some counterthoughts, to do with as you will.  I'm working wioth combat 
skills here, since they seem to be the primary case.  Extrapolation into 
other cases is allowable, even recommended.


Some support skills are really altered attack forms.  Parry and Feint, 
for example, are things you do instead of attacking with your weapon, 
because you think it will help you tactically.  No chance of florentine 
penalties (unless you do several of them at once), because they are 
normal skill uses.  Note that they all affect where the blow lands and/or 
how much it hurts.

Samples: Parry, Feint, Block, Lunge, Great Blow, Roundhouse, others as 
you think of them.

Call Them: Morganatic Skills (just kidding!)  Style skills.

Suggestion: Use weapon skill, with mods for the action and 3%/rank for 
the support skill.
Alternative: Use support skill (with mods for the action) with weapon as 
a secondary.


Other support skills are really separate actions. Combat Maneuver, 
Acrobatics for special attacks, a second weapon skill, or Plane Shift for 
interdimensional Judo are all unrelated (skill-wise) to the use of a 
weapon or attack.  No chance of avoiding florentine penalties here, since 
that's what they're intended for.

Call Them: nothing special.  They're just other skills you happen to be 
using.

Suggestion: Roll support skill as primary, apply florentine mods.


Then there are the other ones.  Skills designed to be used with other 
skills.  Florentince, for instance, or quickstrike.  Their primary effect 
isn't on the attack, but on the mods applying to the attack. Admittedly, 
this is a tough distinction, but it allows, say, the Florentine skill to 
be used without accruing additional Florentine mods.  (That way lies 
madness.)  These are really system-affecting skills, so I would strive to 
keep them free from Florentine penalties.

Call Them: I dunno.  Support Skills.  Mode Skills.  Phred.

Suggestion: Roll support skill as primary, apply SL's to current action 
mods.


