"RE: Spell Batteries and different types of spells.","I also am not an expert on the magic mechanics of the system, but I am
seriously into playability and balance, so here is my 4 cents.

What is the exact difference between a spell trigger and a spell battery
anyway?  Isn't a spell battery just a more general form of a spell trigger?
I generally don't like the concepts of spell batteries, period.  To me it is
more of a balance thing that and actual reason for disliking them.  I just
find them unbalancing as far as play goes.  It is not he will the better
skills or creativity who wins, its he with the most spell batteries.
Anyway, I digress, back to my original thought.

If you go with Alex's concept of 'Angreals' where the battery is more like
an enhancer then spell triggers and batteries are the same thing.  The more
confined the enhancement the more powerful it is.  For example, say Khalid
makes three spell 'triggers' as follows:

1) General will enchancer keyed to himself - This is a very general will
enchancer and is what is considered a battery in the present terms.  It is
keyed to his specific pattern but can be used to enchancer ANY sorcery or
spell up to a certain amount of power.  This item is less structured than
others and so can not enhance that much, say it will output 5 points of
power for even point sent through it.

2) A fire sorcery enchancer - This is a more specific enchancer, much like a
focus, and can be used for any sorcery or spell that uses fire as a base.
The pattern would be keyed to Khalid and to the general pattern for fire.
Because this is a more specific item it has more enhancement properties, say
10 points for every point passed through it.

3) A fire ball spell trigger - This is the most structured of the items and
is an enhancer for one specific pattern.  Because it has only one pattern
associated with it can also be used to shorted the cast time.  It would
still require putting power into it in order to set it off, but may not
necessarily be associated with only one person.  It might have a very high
ratio say 15 to 1.

So there are levels of spell trigger based on the amount of structure they
have.
Level	Effect	Restrictions
1	2-3:1		Can be used by anybody, for anything (General
Battery)
2	2-5:1		Can be used by one person for anything (Individual
battery)
3	3-7:1		Keyed to a general pattern (ie.fire) but usable by
anyone (General focus)
4	5-10:1	Keyed to a specific individual and general pattern
(Individual focus)
5	10-30:1	General Spell trigger (Usable by anyone for a specific
affect)
6	15-40:1	Individual Spell trigger (Usable by specific person for
specific affect)

Obviously, I'm just making up the numbers.

-Britt









