"RE: Spell Batteries and different types of spells.","I like the seperation of magecraft into different aproaches Sorceries vs. 
Incantations vs. Wizardries,  and I am not all all comfortable with lumping 
them all together.  I think the system could work if you used a family 
skill type of modifier but I am lobbying now for a very distant relation, 
20% or 40% tops.  Here (drawing on what I know best) is my rational.

When students learn how to solve an Algebra problem there are three 
different aproaches I try to teach.

The first is an intuitive ""think about it and see if you can figure it out"" 
type of aproach that works best with simple equations i.e. 2x=4.  Lets call 
this S: Problem Solving.

The second is the traditional algebraic skills aproach, in the equation 
above we were all taught to divide both sides by 2 to get the answer.  By 
catagorizing different types of algebraic equations and learning specifc 
aproaches to solving each type ( quadratic as apposed to first degree) a 
student has a good chance of solving equations.  The downside is that it 
takes longer than the intuitive aproach if the problem is easy as in the 
2x=4 example, and does not work if the problem doesn't fit into a catagory 
that is recognised.  This is an I: Problem Solving.

The third and most powerful problem solving technique that math teachers 
teach is the ""guess check and then guess again"" technique.  This will 
always work given enough guesses so it is the most effective, but it is 
very time consuming so I'll call it W: Equation Solving.

If you'll grant me the above analogy, I can assure you that students who 
are good at one type of problem solving are not neccessarily good at 
others.  In fact often the urge to slip into an intuitive approach really 
gets in their way if they try to solve an equation using a different 
strategy.

I think the same would be true of a sorcerer trying to cast a Wizardry 
(there is no such thing as a slight oversight when juggling 800 points of 
power) or the a Wizard who solves the magical equivilent of the equation 
""2x=10,000"" by starting at 1 and trying every number until they get to 
5000.


