"Re: Spell Batteries and different types of spells.","Wow... we seem to have struck system-discussion gold here...


It looks like we have three (there's that number again) discussions going 
on here:

1. Spell batteries vs. spell triggers vs. enhancers (spell and otherwise)

2. Spells vs. sorceries

3. Various categories of spells.


As befits my usual logical approach, I'm going to attack them in random 
order.


SPELLS VS SORCERIES

As I understand it, sorceries are simple magical effects build into our 
concept of Reality.  Anyone with a little bit of magical aptitude can 
learn the whole array of them.  They are simple effects (though, with 
enough power and ingenuity in their use, possibly quite effective).  They 
do not require the caster to be linked to any particular power-pattern 
for their use.

Spells are wizard-designed sub-patterns that are more versatile, more 
complex, and more unnatural (to the current Reality) than sorceries.  
They range in complexity from the simple (a more efficient sorcery, or a 
combination of sorceries) to the complex (arcane and mysterious rituals 
producing quite unique effects).  They take more time than sorceries, 
they require some form of wizardric connection, and they can be quite 
subtle and powerful. 

Sorcery is a paranatural ability.  Spells are a wizardric creation based 
on the patterns they link to.  That, at least is my take on the matter.  





VARIOUS CATEGORIES OF SPELLS

Right now, as I understand it, Alex is calling all the spells 'workings' 
as a class, and breaking them up into 'spells', 'rituals', 'rites', and 
'incantations' (formerly 'invokations').  At the moment, I believe these 
to be separate skills with some nebulous crossover effect, but I could be 
mistaken.

Various people have proposed various changes to the (apparently 
little-liked) current system.  I see little reason to stay out of the 
fray.  Here is what I would like to see:

A change in nomenclature-- call them 'simple spells', 'complex spells', 
'simple rituals', and  'complex rituals'.  I think the names are more 
obvious in their progression, and better reflect what is coing on.  
('Rite', for instance, has religious implications, and 'incantation' does 
not sound like it takes a long time or required anything in the way of 
material components.)

A change in labelling-- list them as 'M1:', 'M2:', 'M3:', and 'M4:'.  
This will leave the progression a little more clear, and sets the ground 
for my next proposal.

An added restriction-- require two ranks of an appropriate Wizardry for 
each step.  Simple Spells (M1:) would need two levels of Wizardry, etc, 
etc, up to Complex Rituals (M4:) needing rank 8 in the Wizardry.  This 
meshes with Alex's declared levels of familiarity (rank 2) and 
mastery-enough-not-to-get-confused-when-learning-other-Wizardries (rank 
8).  Whether this restriction works by fiat (you can't) or by penalty 
(here are the minuses) is left as an excercise for the stu-- er, Master.

A definition of relationship-- let these various categories be related 
skills.  If I have a simple ritual that summons an elemental and binds 
them to my will, and I need to do it at the speed of a complex spell, I 
take -20%.  If I want to do a simple spell as a complex ritual, I would 
take -60%.  Perhaps skills in Ritual Design and/or Spell Design could 
reduce this.  Perhaps they'd be required to do it at all.  

A definition of concept-- all these workings (whatever we call them) are 
limited to wizards.  The easiest reason I can think of for this is that 
they are a partial representation of the power-patterns that wizards are 
linked to.  Unlinked beings don't have access to these patterns (at least 
not on a personal basis) and thus can't use these sub-patterns.  The 
level of working (M1-M4) would then represent the closeness of the 
sub-pattern to the major pattern.  Since these patterns are unnatural to 
Reality, more effort (time, will, elaborate preparation) is required to 
manage a major manifestation than a minor one.  


SPELL BATTERIES, ETC, ETC.

I'd like to add some fuel to the fire here by asking Alex to consider the 
role of 'focus' in all of this mess.  Maybe even 'familiars'.  From what 
you've said, it looks like a look at all the mage-enhancing techniques 
might be in order.

Other than that, I'd like to point out that a spell-trigger to 'store 
power' and 'channel power' should not be that tricky for a good Binder.  
Aside from the restrictions on decay-of-spell and all that, I think they 
are easier for an ordinary wizard to produce than some sort of 
will-enhancing powerstone or a reality-mass-enhancing sandbag.


But that's enough for today.  

                      -Myth, the over-opinionated.



