"Re: Spell Batteries and different types of spells.","I am not entirely attached to the ""similarity"" of rites and rituals and I
certainly agree that Sorcery and ""Workings/Rituals/Rite/Incantations"" are
two completely separate beasts.  I think a large part of it is that I
disagree with your analogy.  I think the distinction you make between type 2
and type 3 is not a working vs. ritual kind of distinction but more a
comparison of two completely different styles of spell (and I hope the brute
force kind is rare in magic).

I will attempt to mangle your analogy as follows:

SORCERY
Some students use the intuitive approach (I look at it and see if I can
figure it out).  Of these some react to the form of the equation and some
happen to try the ""obvious"" numbers until they get one that works.  In both
cases they are relying on intuition.

WORKING
Some students look at the equation and attempt to solve it by selecting the
correct formula from a memorized lookup list.  In some sense they are doing
the same thing as the sorcery example except instead of guessing the answer
they are guessing the solution strategy.
e.g.
    Things like ...    x=ny        are solved by...    y=x/n
                            ax^2 +bx +c = 0                 x = (-b +-
qrt( b^2 - 4ac))/2a
(Did I get that right?  It has been a while).

RITUAL/RITE/INCANTATION
The students perform the same actions as above but they recognize and use
intermediate goals (which could lead to blind alleys and retries but we hope
not).  Thus we start with ax^2 + bx +c= 0 and where a,b and c are integers
we first factor out a and if b/a and c/a are still integral we might expand
the factors of b/c and look for patterns, etc.  Same rough actions as above
except that we are doing a much more complex things.  Not only are we
recognizing solutions and strategies but we are recognizing promising
intermediate goals.  While these are different actions I do not think they
use phenominally different skills.  I think in order to get to step C it is
(a) harder and (b) you need to have the basic distinction intermediate goal
as well as a lot more experience under your belt.

Therefor I would say the above off the cuff discussion would indicate that
the following model would apply.

You have a skill in each magical effect you want to produce.
You have a skill in Working, Rite, Ritual and Incantation (or maybe Fire
Working, whatever)
To cast a working you must have rank in the effect and rank in working.
To cast an incantation you must have rank 6 in the effect and rank in
incantation.

Naah, never mind, I don;t like that.  I think the W: skill already has built
in minimums for casting rites, etc.. and that solves the problem just fine.
I don;t think we need extra mechanics.

