Oddly enough, this Dorian mage, member of one of the most recent
schools invented, has asked some of those same questions.

According to my understanding, languages gain power as they are
used.  Repeated bringing-to-mind of a concept, together with the
verbalization of a word or phrase, eventually establishes a
connection between the concept and the word.  As time passes and
the process continues, the link grows stronger.  Eventually, the
verbal component is sufficient to invoke the concept.  At this
point, spells can safely be defined in the language.  Less safely
if the speakers were sloppy thinkers, more safely if the speakers
were all dead, and not continuing to modify the language.

(I'd imagine this is all modified by the reality-mass of the
speakers involved. Interestingly, Alex has said that some
languages needed to be abandoned after developing too much
significance.  Imagine ordering groceries and accidentally
triggering a fireball spell...)

The Dorian Weaver school was founded with Ancient Dorian as a
casting language because it had been well-used my
Reality-affecting people, had lots of concepts for using with
magic, and was a dead language, fairly rigidly-defined, at the
time.

Runes, as far as I know, grow from specialized wizard-marks (much
like mathematical symbology).  The Dorian Weaver school uses
Weaver Runes, developed for the school from the more general
Symbian runes in widespread use around the Free States.  Rune sets
are designed for use with magic, and quickly acquire the necessary
significance by being used by wizards for specific magic-charged
purposes, although I'd imagine a few lean years for a new school
as their runes get charged up with Meaning.

(And all this is only true until Alex says otherwise, as usual.)


