"Re[2]: BT Magic","     If I may weigh in on this topic:  Based on my understanding about how 
     any technical jargon is constructed over time, I would point out that 
     (now) ancient spells constructed in (now) ancient Dorian, were 
     probably not the same as the (then) modern Dorian as spoken by the 
     commoners at the time.  
     
     Much more likely is that mages used or bent certain terms and phrases  
     into a different sense to achieve the desired spell effect.  I would 
     suspect that, for the average (then) modern speaker of Dorian, the 
     words and phrases of the mages would be recognizable as Dorian, but - 
     as in any technical argot - would not necessarily make any sense in 
     the way they were used.  
     
     I would agree that it would be a difficult task to create spells in 
     (now) modern Dorian - not because modern languages, per se, are not 
     adequate, but because they don't already have a rich body of 
     distinctions in that specific area.  Inventing spell language from 
     scratch that was powerful, appropriate and useful in (now) modern 
     Dorian would most probably require the services of a superior 
     philosopher or poet.  
     
     [ron] 
     
     


