"Re: BT Magic: Some elaboration. ","     This opens up a very interesting line of inquiry:  If, as it has been 
     outlined, spells gain their effect not from tapping 'a priori'  
     physical principles and laws, but through the combined effect of a) 
     time, b) number of conversations and, presumably, c) the status or 
     prestige of the speakers - then an interesting opening is created:  
     
     It is possible for an extraordinary being to arise, outside usual 
     expectation, who embodies a spectacular gift for enrolling others in a 
     new reality-agreement.  (I am thinking of a similar character - the 
     'Mule' - from the Foundation series).  Despite the massive momentum 
     that the current reality-agreement enjoys, it is conceivable for a 
     local character of superior talent to create quite a local disruption, 
     and even perhaps, threaten the prevailing order.  
     
     Has this already happened within the scenario's current historical 
     time?  Are their any safeguards or checks-and-balances to contain such 
     a threat?  Certainly, given a long enough span of time, the odds of 
     such a rogue appearing are statistically significant.  
     
     Alternatively, there could be some subversive sect that has been 
     preserving their unique rituals over an impossibly long period of 
     time.  I imagine them practicing their craft in caves and dive bars, 
     generation after generation, stubbornly refusing to yield to the 
     prevailing conversation.  
     
     Couldn't a historically significant swelling of their ranks threaten 
     (or at least challenge) the current pattern of magic speaking?  Or, 
     maybe another way to say it is:  Their speaking is already a minor 
     part of the reality-agreement pattern - could it become dominant over 
     time?  
      
     (musings from the dark and far away...)
     
     [ron]


