"History","Hi Alex,

I am considering starting on a new project (related to and in fact inspired by the Wizardry project).  I would like to write a couple of stories that flesh out the history of the Kua-Tao a little more.  I know this is a potential mine field since they are the oldest culture I know of and therefor lost in the murky depths of too many reality shifts but I think this may actually be an advantage since therefor nothing I say needs to be true or relevant.  What do you think?

If you think YES Jim should write some histories continue.
If you think NO Jim should not write some histories e-mail a reply now.

The premise to the stories that I was going to write were vignettes which set the mood and historical context for different stages of the Sigmund enitities life.  I see these occuring in three sets:
    a.. Random observations of an unnamed Kua-Toa who acts mostly as an observer
    b.. Random observations of Nuryev at the time of the creation of the Tharuden schools/Creation of the Ward/Battle against the Golden One.  This is a little more active and a little less observer oriented.
    c.. Randon observations of Sigmund in the present.  This will be tales of what I have done.
These three sets would involve three world views:
    a.. View One - Some time in the prior cycle involving the Kua-Toa high court and the Kua-Toa-Slaad wars and the discovery of the Dragons.  This would be told from the perspective of a world so different as to be barely recognizable.  The assumption (on my part) would be that there would be some great terminal event (such as a huge battle) that caused an end to this cycle and replaced it with a history already in progress which is the current cycle.
    b.. View Two - Some time in the current cycle which is during the Chaos Wars (according to Jim - I had a little terminology confusion).  This would center around the time that I was active in Tharuden and when the five were building the ward.  My assumption is that for me personally my start of activity in this cycle would immediately follow the end of the last cycle and yet a large amount of history which is different from the history of the last cycle and yet involves the same characters (like Dau-Pen) would already have occured (entry into a history in progress).
    c.. View Three - The present.  I would treat the present as existing within the same cycle as view two in that much of the world involves the same characters and places (although at least one key ocean has moved).  I would not treat view two as a straight historical predecessor to the present since to many reality shifts have intervened.
In general I would treat the three points as seperate islands of localized interest without concentrating two much on how one view came into being based on another view.  It is almost gauranteed that the perception of the past in the later views would conflict with the perception of the present in the earlier views.  I would also always be telling stories from the perspective of the events as I think the 'Sigmund' perspective would have been.

If you think YES Jim should write some histories from these perspectives continue.
If you think Jim should write some histories from some of these perspectives but not others e-mail a reply now.
If you think NO Jim should not write some histories from these perspectives e-mail a reply now.

If you got this far I am psyched.  I have a number of ideas for basic guidelines that will allow me to be creative without defining to much or stepping on other peoples viewpoints.  Some of these include the following things:

The Kua-Toa are an arrogant culture and consider the only other real culture worth interacting with to be the Slaad and then only to kill them.  Still a Kua-Toa would rather talk to a Slaad then one of those animals like humans or dragons (a very powerful and intelligent animal true but just not socially evolved - sniff).  As such there is a huge amount of things which a Kua-Toa historian would just gloss over as unimportant neither defining or precluding a large number of significant historical events.

I see the end of the last cycle as a terminal event that involves a retroactive rewriting of history to create a past involving many of the same actors with completely different events.  As such when Nuryev pops into the world it is no suprise that the Dragons are much more powerful, that humans are starting to populate everywhere and even build cities and that the true denizens of the world are very hard to find (although there mark is very strong in the form of the Golden Empire and the reality structure present).  BTW:  Can you tell that I just finished the Wheel of Time.

I have a ton more ideas but why dont I wait to get your initial feedback.


 


