"Re: Knoife","Heres what I was planning.

Since I am publishing as web pages and I do not have a convenient real-time db<->web page link at the moment I was not going to support searches.  Instead I was going to support a concept of threads.

The main history would be output as a single list of major chronological events formatted as it currently is on the web page.

Following the chronological list I was going to have a series of threads each corresponding to a significant name, person or group.

I was imagining threads as working in one of two ways:

In both cases you would start a thread by creating a major name for it (like Aeroch or Shape Shifters, etc.)

In the manual case you would then attach all relevant events to the thread by linking them (rather than having attributes).  From a database point of view the distinction is that you don;t have to change the schema every time you add a new thread since the connections is via a link record rather than a fixed field in the schema.  The disadvantage is that the UI for specifiying these things is more awkward and the use case probably ends up being (1) define event (2) individually add event to each thread it relates to.  This is a multi-stage process and more likely to ""miss"" relevant events but is simpler to implement and requires less maintance from a db persepective (more for a data perspective).

I am also thinking of implementing an automatic case.  In this case you not only enter a single word thread name but also a number of aliases for the thread.  I would then build an automatic process which would run through every event in the Db and link up to the thread any event which contained something from the word list for the thread. This is much easier to maintain from a data perspective since you can always wipe out all of the thread links and regenerate them.  It does suffer from the hazard of false hits (events at which Sigmund's Sword of Aeroch play a part show up on the thread for Aeroch) and much more common frequent misses (it will take a while for all of the Forsetti and City of Law references to show up, mis spelling becomes more deadly and some links will just not be practical - e.g. Blade of Stone = Kheldar?).

Despite its limitations I am leaning towards the latter.  The whole idea of both of them is rather than interactive searches pre-run all of the common searches and store them as historical pathways through the growing mass of events.

Actually, I just realized to make the whole auto-search thing manageable I can just include a Db field for non-displayed tags that is searched when generating thread contents.  Then you can always override to include something in a thread.  And I dont think there is anything wrong with over-reporting events.  Just dont name any major historical figure ""The"" or ""NaMed"".

Initial threads (once I implement all of this of course) would be:

Shape Shifters
  ShapeShifters, Mordenaith, Morphus, Kheldar, Odin?, Wotan?, Sigmund, Nuryev?, Kilsorana, Khalid, Erithmaeon, E-Man, Catbird, Dullo, Arak, Singing Warrior, Vartigan
The Five
  Falstaff, Kheldar, Logos, Rhismaeon, Nuryev, Sigmund, Linking Ward
Elves
  Faer-Han, Quentar, Golden Ones,...
Gray Wanderers
MKP
Aeroch & Hiemdell

Atlernatively I do have 5 boolean fields associated with each record at the moment and I could provide mega threads for each of these topics:

    IsGods - All events related to gods
    IsPolitics - All events related to kingdoms and rulership
    IsRaces - All events related to race creation/evolution
    IsPeople - All events related toi specific peoples major timelines (birth, death, crowned king,...)
    IsMagic - All events related to the history of magic
