"Elvish Magic","Jim - I CC'd you to promote feedback but do not panic if what I say is different than were you were going.  I am just playing and I acknowedge that it is your sandbox.

I just had a long discussion with Jim about what elvish magic is all about and I came to the conclusion that I will have to have my own internal view if I want to make any sense about anything.  Out of our discussion I did glean the following things:

All great inventions throughout history were actually made by elves even if later attributed to other people.
High Elves can choose whether to use the Order/Chaos based patterns or to use 'Naming'
Gray Elves have no choice and must use 'Naming'
'Naming' essentially means playing with other peoples toys.  As in naming is a way to deal with other power patterns (Kua-Toa/Slaad and possibly Draconic according to him) and produce effects.  Elvish magic by itself NEVER produces any effects except at the discipline level.
Elvish magic never persists outside of the Aura/Concentration of the caster unless it is supported by someone else.
Elves alter reality easier than sneezing but it does not last as described above.

This view of elven magic was not particularly useful to me.  It does not really give any unique character to elven magic at all.  As such I came up with the following alternate viewpoint which I believe encompasses the same set of facts.

[SLIGHT ASIDE] Before starting into that I thought I should mention something about the word pattern.  It seems to figure heavily into Jim's concept of elven magic.  I would assert that wizardry patterns refer to Kua-Toa created.  Specifically all of the human wizardries are called power patterns becuase they have some aspect of Order magic in them (even Illusion which is why humans do not go insane casting it - although the order magic here is probably the slimmest of frameworks).  As far as the other types of magic I would say that Dreaming does not really fit the word pattern, it is a fundamentally different thing.  Where Slaad influences have appeared in the human wizardries it is like a mold or a virus or a taint on the underlying Ordered framework and in the case of Illusion the infection is bigger than the thing it infects.  In a similar sense I would say that Draconic magic is so fundamentally different than Order magic that a pure draconic archetype would never be described as a pattern (although there may be achetypical patterns or archetypical patterners as well as infected archetypes and archetypical infections).  What I am trying to do is establish the fundamental difference between the types of magic.

Having said all of that let us return to elvish magic:

My impression of elivsh magic from the way that it has occured in the world is that it deals with anima. (Kua-Toa=Objective World, Slaad=Dream, Dragon=Archetype, Elf=Anima).  As such an elvish approach to magic would be to treat everything in the world as an animate entity and interact with it appropriately.  Sing to the trees and ask them to grow a certain way.  Sing to the crystals and ask them to grow a certain way.  Talk to the stars and ask them for prophecies. etc.

Where does Jim and Naming fit into this.  My contention is that Mordenaith is not a generalist elven mage but in fact an extreme specialist.  He specializes in talking with human wizardry patterns and asking them to do things for him.  In doing this he has developed the whole specialized vocabulary of naming and tweaking patterns and verbs, etc.  In fact a true generalist elven mage would talk to anything.  Why ask the geomatic pattern to make a wall when you can just ask the earth to rise up and form itself into a wall?  The reason is that since Mordenaith specializes he is MUCH more fluent in the language and interactions of patterns, they are pretty powerful and talking to the earth is probably slower and more likely to give you lip about doing stuff.  I would suspect that most elven mages specialize not becuase the fundamental actions are different but because it is important to know the specific thing you are talking to VERY well.  As a special case of this elvish enchantment is probably not ussualyy done by talking the the enchantment pattern but ussually done by talking to humans and having a (strangely elvish in viewpoint) knowledge of human interactions.

As such I would propose that an elvish mage would have skills like the following:
A W:skill in the voice being used (for Jim power patterns may be one voice, for an earthsinger earth might be a voice)
A lore skill (G: or not?)  in each kind of thing being talked to (for Jim each power pattern e.g. Levator, for an earthsinger each kind of earth.  I plan on Stone, Metal, Crystal and Earth(i.e.Dirt)).
A variety of interaction within that voice (for jim the set of verbs, for an earth singer another set of verbs like grow, animate, take the form of, have the senses of, ...)

The verbs are the part I am least sure about becuase I am not sure I have distinguished between them and the sorceries.

In this way Sigmund would be an EarthSinger in the same way that Mordenaith is a Namer and they would both be elven magics.  As a side note I do not see elven magics as having a pattern anymore than draconic or slaad magic.  What would it have?  Community is the wrong word.  I will have to think about that.  For the moment lets call it a spiritview (please replace this term).  

It is interesting to think then:  Mordenaith deals with the spiritview of patterns, is there a pattern for spiritviewing (healing or necromancy?), can you have a tainted spritiview or an archetypical spiritview?  Does an archetype have a spirit (independant of its Avatars?).

