Subject: Let's do the time warp again ...


    I've been giving the situation a considerable amount of thought.
With regards to running the other groups (and determining the actions of
the NPC's) I'd like to present you with some possibilities.  I'm also
confused about the concept of ""different realities"".

    I thought that you had said that although there might be other
realities populated by other Wills, their reality would be so alien to
ours that there could never be crossover because neither of us could
conceive of the other.  I'm fairly certain that I must have that wrong
because of what happened in the last run, as well as the whole Star Trek
bug incursion.

    With regards to issue of where/when we are, there are three
possibilities that I can think of.  The first is that temporally we are
in the same ""time"" as we were before I blew us up but we are in a
reality formed around the Wills of the Slaad that ""ceased to exist"" in
the Epoch 3 transition.

    It came to me that in each Epoch transition we have talked about
massive deaths occurring among the ""children"" of the Elder Gods.
Assuming that the whole multi-Epoch ""Elder Gods"" concept isn't a recent
reality creation, I would expect that in most of those cases the Elder
Gods deliberately re-absorbed the wills of those who ""didn't make it"" so
that they could have more energy for the next phase.

    But it is entirely possible that many of those Wills simply couldn't
make the paradigm shift to the new reality of the consensus.  If that is
the case it would have created a splinter (pocket) reality where they
continued to exist as they had before.  I believe that this explanation
is not where/when we are, but rather the description of the source of
the recent incursion.

    The second possibility is that we are in a different phase (time) of
""our"" reality.  This seems highly unlikely since it has been made quite
clear that there is sufficient difference between Epoch 5, Epoch 4, and
Epoch 3, that there is no way to ""shift phase"" to the earlier ""time"".

    What intrigues me, though, is a contemplation of time travel as it
relates to reality in your world.  After multiple conversations I think
that most of us are pretty clear that the ""reality"" around us is an
agreement, a ""consensus"", between all of the Wills that make up that
consensus.  And that ""time"" is a way of grouping interactions between
those Wills in a sequential fashion.  Since the reality of ""now"" is no
more than the consensus agrees it to be, if the consensus supports the
""rule"" of time travel and the mutability of ""events"", then it must also
agree to change the parameters of ""now"" if the parameters of the ""past""
are changed.

    We have discussed what happens to a ""weak"" Will if the ""body"" dies
(usually absorbed by a ""god"").  We have discussed what the agreement
says happens when an entity has been Be Not'd - although I don't believe
that I have ever seen or discussed a quantitative analysis of what
happens to the Will in a Be Not situation.  We have touched on the
practice of the Gods of ""seeding"" the world with ""young"" Wills and then
""harvesting"" experienced Wills at the end of their life span.  Given the
""reality"" of ""time"" travel, and the ability to interact with someone who
is ""currently"" ""dead"", there *must* be continuity of Will on an ""entity""
basis.  We have discussed that Greater Gods don't have the ability to
create individual Wills (instead influencing the ""Overmind"" to do so).

    I wonder, though, what is actually happening when the ""overmind""
creates a being.  And does ANY entity have the power to uncreate a
being?  If an entity is Be Not'd, has it been ""destroyed""?  Or is that
the consensus has merely been persuaded that the entity does not exist
and therefore it has been excluded from the consensus; shunned/ignored.
Yet if there is some continuity of Will through different entities, and
one of those entities is Be Not'd, the Will which made up the Be Not'd
entity was another entity ""before"" and another entity ""after"".  What
happened to the Will in between?

    Ok, so maybe I've made a few points, but where am I going with this?

    The use of the word ""Epoch"" is deceptive.  In a ""world"" where time
travel exists, but only as a ""dimension"" of the mind, Epoch implies
""time"".  We're told that the reality difference prevents time travel
between Epoch's.  Yet, given the parameters that I discussed earlier, a
Will which exists in more than one time is still the same Will.

    Doesn't this imply that a Will that exists in more than one Epoch is
still the same Will?  And if it is, does that not imply that, at the
very least, those Wills which exist in more than one Epoch should be
able to ""shift their mental focus"" (move) between those Epoch's?  I
think that it does.  But if you want to move from one Epoch to another,
time travel isn't going to get you there.  That would be like trying to
take a plane to get to the moon.  You need to use a different method.

    I think that the entities that are aware of how to move from one
Epoch to another a) for some reason don't want to make reverse
transitions and b) don't want others to make reverse transitions.  One
reason might be related to a consensus version of ""Entropy"".  Entities
that travel in time take their ""power"" with them.  This is fine because
time is a consensus ""illusion"".  But entities that translate to the
previous Epoch may be ""leaving something behind"".  All entities know
what the world has history even if they don't know the ""history of the
world"".  Yet how many entities have any idea about the Epoch's?  We've
been lead to believe that that number is extremely low.

    If that is the case, then the consensus does not support Epoch
translations - in either direction.  So not only is it more difficult to
make the transition (because you aren't getting help from the
consensus), any power that you control  which is actually group driven
(Wizardry, Divine Magic, and most Gift Magic; possibly Alchemy,
Thaumaturgy, Natural Magics, Craft Magics, Incarnate Magic - even the
Laws of Magic themselves) might be limited or non-existent.

    Further, causality is also a consensus effect.  Thus, if there is no
awareness of other Epochs, then there will be no change to the
parameters of Epoch 5 if the parameters of Epoch 4 are changed.  Put
another way, there will be no change to the parameters of Epoch Blue if
the parameters of Epoch Yellow are changed.  That means that unless
Kheldar enrolls a significant portion of this reality, Kheldar can not
affect the Epoch 5 reality at all.  Nor can we ride out the end of Epoch
3 to 4 or 4 to 5.  If we are in Epoch 3 then we will be trying to
survive Epoch 3 until WE make the transition to another reality.

    From a strictly character oriented framework, if what I've
postulated were actually the case then only minor skills learned in this
Epoch would translate back with us.  And only because our characters
would seed the consensus of Epoch 5 with the knowledge that we had
gained in skills.

    On the other hand, transition from one Epoch to another is likely to
have its advantages for us, too.  From what I've said above, it must
require a method different from ""Temporal Magic"".  And since the
occurrence of Epoch travel is extremely rare, it implies that there are
no fixed parameters regarding the effects of Epoch travel.  It is
probably a lot like the space travel in ""Hitchhikers Guide to the
Galaxy"".  In fact, Alex set me on this track when he talked about the
Slaad Conjuration Gateway.  He said something about anything in the gate
being 50% probable.

    If we are able to return to Epoch 5, using some form of ""probability
travel"", and we prep ourselves for the instant of transition, then we
may be able to ""create"" or alter something about ourselves or the
reality of Epoch 5 simply because the consensus will be open to the
possibility of anything from entities that have done what was agreed to
be impossible.

    There is a scary corollary to this, though.  Something that would
explain why we haven't heard about Epoch travel occurring.  If Epoch
travel is accomplished by means of ""probability travel"" and a consensus
version of Entropy, then it may be more possible for a small group,
using a lot of energy, to move ""back"" to a more ""chaotic"" Epoch which
""accepts"" the possibility.  It is much more unlikely that a small group
would be able to make a transition to a more ordered Epoch - one which
didn't believe that such transitions were possible.  It is likely that
the ""easiest"" way to move to a more ordered Epoch would be as part of a
mass consensus change in that direction.  That being said, we may wish
to hope that we are indeed at the ""temporal"" end of Epoch 3, with most
of the Wills preparing to transition to a more ordered state.

    This has been the most philosophic that I have ever been in my life
and I am now going to drive home and go to bed.

    Chris

