stand-up philosophers) there are several theories about
parallel/branching worlds that don't contradict known physics.
(Admittedly, most of their evidence is conveniently located in a
parallel universe, where we can't see it, but still...)

Me, I'll stick with the old consensus-building adage:  ""If you can't
tell, it doesn't matter.""



> >The consensus is not intrinsically sacred, it is an agreed
> >upon fiction that gets revised every time someone breaks it.
> >Atoms were the smallest indivisible particle of matter until
> >60 odd years ago, and so on.

> THE UNIVERSE will still have been the same, even if we didn't
> understand it yet.

<shrug>

What practical difference does it make?  To the total extent of our
understanding at one point, the sun revolved around the earth, and the
stars were graven on crystal spheres held, for all I know, by angels.
To the total extent of our understanding now, the earth revolves
around the sun, and stars are huge balls of fusing hydrogen plasma
incredibly far away.

If you want, you can posit that there was a reality shift, so now the
sun was now 'always' a ball of gas (and may have been something else
in an earlier reality), or you can say that the first assumption was
incorrect, and we now have a clearer view of the process than our
imaginative ancestors.  Either way, daylight comes and goes, and the
stars shine down on us all.

While I see your point that it is extremely unlikely two astronauts
will go up and one of them will bump into a crystal sphere while the
other spends many years traveling very fast only to fall into a
distant sun, for all practical purposes (astronauts still being a
minute percentage of the populace) it just doesn't matter!

There may be one ""true"" underlying universe.  There may be a
hodgepodge of fuzzy, ill-defined personal universes that negotiate
most of their interactions.  I suspect the BT universe is somewhere
between those two options.  But all we know is that this is the way
things behave.  Here (the 'real world', not to be confused with
anything produced by MTV), as well as there (the BT world, rather
easily confused by Player Characters.)

Note that even in a 'hodgepodge' model, one might require certain
commonalities to interact at all, like arm-flapping not equaling
flight.  OTOH, since you would be dwelling in your own universe, you
might simply not perceive the flight (since it's defined for you as
impossible), and judge the flapping man to be quite mad.  Anything
else might require an external force to change your personal universe
(an entirely different feat), or for you to give up your cozy little
universe and venture into unknown Realities.  (And no, I neither know
how to do that or suggest that it would be a Good Idea.  Though it
seems the sort of thing that a Shifter would try.)

Again, if you can't tell, it doesn't matter.  (The corollary being
that it it's that important, you should find a way to tell.)



> >I know several people you reflect the common world view that you
> >CANNOT live without money. The fact that money or our current
scheme
> >of capitalism is a recent invention bounces off their belief. We
are
> >talking people that are very intelligent. For me , at least, it is
