I had an odd character concept/plot twist for a character in Alex's world.
It is based on the following presumption:

 

Most characters which are related to Death are ussually characterized as
evil (excepting of course current party members/deities of the dead).  It
occured to me that philosophically you could have a religous paladin of
death who was impersonal rather than evil based on the following argument:

 

There is a certain class of death I will call environmental death (disease,
hunger, hypothermia,...) which is distinct from violent death or other
direct killing by a CGB*.  In general we can say that environmental death is
based on locations and occurs because the dead person was not suitable for
the environment.  One question that comes from this is why should such harsh
environments exist?  In a consensus reality we can conclude that the
statement ""a person dies of thirst in the desert because it is a harsh
environment"" is motivated by the consensus asserting that ""deserts are harsh
environments"" or ""deserts are places were people die"".  Why then would the
consensus want to make locations were people die?  One reason would be crowd
control.  Planar theory says that we generate the physical world around us
to suit our needs.  Perhaps plagues and hunger in overcrowded cities is just
the consensus' way to encourage us to spread out a little.  Perhaps deserts
and arctic tundras are the consensus' way to get us not to spread out to
much.  After all, the prime leads us to believe that each location must have
a location next to it (no one has yet found and edge) therefor the only
thing that prevents us from spreading out infintiley far from each other is
that environments become to harsh and we become over extended.  In other
words we face death.  Environmental death is not an immediate thing.  It
comes on gradually giving us plenty of time to recognize the error of our
ways and move to a more suitable location.

 

Possesing this attitude a death-paladin would feel more like a shepard than
a homicidal maniac.  In fact this death-paladin might even regret it when
people die.  Sort of along the lines of ""well I gave them a lot of warnings
but they ignored it.  Mores the pity.""

 

 

