"Gaming - The fourth epoch transition","In my last post I had sort of glossed over the fourth epoch.  This was
because I was less certain of what was going on there than in the others.
Based on the fundamental conflict viewpoint that I had put forward in my
Theory of Magic I think I have discovered the fundamental conflict of the
fourth epoch.

One of my core historical assumptions is that you don't get an epoch change
unless there is a fundamental shift in the nature of reality. Otherwise it
would just be an era shift, or even just time passing.  Therefor there must
be something fundamentally different between the fourth and the fifth epoch.
With one, two and three I have painted this as existence, individuality and
a consensus.  All three of these are MAJOR concept shifts.  It is difficult
for me to come up with something as fundamental for the fourth epoch
transition but here goes.

The key to the conflicts in the first three epochs is the evolution of
being.  The closer that you get to the present the harder it is to
distinguish the fundmanental precept changes that characterize that
evolution.  If we look at the artifacts (things left over) of the fourth
epoch however the major one which stands out for me is the balance.

[I assume the balance is a fourth epoch creation for most people.  I also
assume that the gates of Chronos and the Bifrost are fifth epoch creations.
Are the gates fourth?]

The key operational principle of the balance is individual moderation.  One
way to look at the balance is to view it as a tool that prevents any one
entity from having an inordinate amount of control on the consensus.
Another way to look at it is that it is a tool that discourages the forces
on the consensus from being to centralized (controlled by a small number of
wills).  From this perspective the balance can be seen as yet another swing
of the pendulum.  The pendulum being the following progression:

1.    Existence - Pro-Unity Anti-Entropy (if you consider the ultimate
entropic state = heat death = non-existence)
2.    Individuality - Anti-Unity Pro-Entropy (a greater number of smaller
individuals = more chaos and fragmentation)
3.    Consensus - Pro-Unity Anti-Entropy (a consensus promotes uniformity
which counters fragmentation)
4.    Balance - Anti-Unity Pro-Entropy (a balance prevents ""clumping"" and
promotes more diversity)

>From the perspective of conflict resolution this seems to fit the bill for
an epoch transition but it still does not fit the metaphysical requirement
of a fundamental change in perspective.  Perhaps part of the reason this is
hard is that I may have jumped to far ahead in the third epoch transition.

When the Kua-Toa created the UniverseNet they created a consensus which
allowed individuals to live in a reality that all could agree on.  Implicit
in this design is a restorative force that attempts to forcefully bring the
individual into alignment with the consensus.  It may have been erroneous to
identify this force with temporality and causality.  Or more precisely it
may have been correct to identify it with temporality as a now measurable
concept but not with causality.

Causality is a specific ordering proposition that drastically reduces the
number of possible presents based on past events.  Another way to look at
this is that causality makes a requirement that the farther back you change
an event (the more fundamental a change is) the more force is required to
accomplish it.  At the surface this sounds like a necessary property of the
basic UniverseNet and in fact it must have been.  Operationally however it
is likely that for the majority of the fourth epoch time travel was
drastically easier and the nature of reality had not reached the stability
of its current expression.

And in fact this is the key.  The second fundamental concept of the fourth
epoch (besides the balance) is the prime.  The prime as we know it today is
a function of the bifrost but the fact is that by the very nature of humans
the fundamental concept of primeness must have been the establishing concept
of the fifth epoch.  The core of primeness has to do with the path of
reality.  Without primeness you could have a consensus that, at any point in
time, was shared by all people to some degree, but which over time wandered
all over the realm of possibility.  With primeness the character of the
universe from one moment to the next will follow an orderly progression and
the past will appear fairly similar to the present.  In fact the nature of
primeness can probably be stated as ""the consensus view of the present will
always have the appearance of being the logical progression of the past"".  I
am havinbg trouble getting a good sound bite here but I think this is the
core concept.

This function (making the present seem to follow logically from the past)
may be the thing that causes people to forget the old past when they fail
there save vs.  a reality alteration.  This might not be a necessary
consequence of reality alteration itself.  I can also see how primeness and
the balance are integrally related.

Hmmm, I must think about this more.  This could even change my view of the
advisability of submitting to the balance.

Once I have all of these thoughts coherent I will fold them back into my
theory of magic document just so I can keep a single repository.

